1
00:00:09,384 --> 00:00:11,093
AUDREY WELLS: The book
Under the Tuscan Sun

2
00:00:11,177 --> 00:00:13,053
was sent to me early in 2001

3
00:00:13,138 --> 00:00:15,931
to see if I wanted to adapt it
into a screenplay.

4
00:00:16,016 --> 00:00:17,182
And I was aware of the book.

5
00:00:17,267 --> 00:00:20,310
I knew it had been a best-seller
for many months.

6
00:00:20,395 --> 00:00:24,565
I read it and found that it had
real evocative power for me.

7
00:00:24,649 --> 00:00:26,859
It was a memoir, really,
written by Frances Mayes

8
00:00:26,943 --> 00:00:29,778
about buying a rundown villa
in Tuscany

9
00:00:29,863 --> 00:00:33,907
and how the process of restoring it
sent her deep into Italian culture.

10
00:00:33,992 --> 00:00:36,702
And it was a dense,
poetic piece of work

11
00:00:36,786 --> 00:00:37,953
that was beautiful to read,

12
00:00:38,038 --> 00:00:41,665
but contained nothing resembling
conventional screenplay structure.

13
00:00:41,750 --> 00:00:44,376
At the time, however, l was
working on an idea of my own

14
00:00:44,461 --> 00:00:45,919
about a woman
overcoming heartbreak.

15
00:00:46,004 --> 00:00:49,506
And I started to realize that these
two stories could be combined.

16
00:00:49,591 --> 00:00:52,718
That I could take the instigating
incident in Frances' book,

17
00:00:52,802 --> 00:00:55,304
buying a villa in Tuscany,
getting a clean slate,

18
00:00:55,388 --> 00:00:56,847
starting your life in a new way.

19
00:00:56,931 --> 00:01:01,435
And I could combine that with the
elements that I had in my other story.

20
00:01:01,811 --> 00:01:04,271
I met Frances Mayes in Tuscany

21
00:01:04,355 --> 00:01:07,399
and she was well aware that
whoever was going to adapt her story

22
00:01:07,484 --> 00:01:10,069
was going to have to bring
something big to the table.

23
00:01:10,153 --> 00:01:13,530
She knew that someone
would need to bring plot,

24
00:01:13,615 --> 00:01:17,576
and different characters,
and she was very, very open to that.

25
00:01:17,660 --> 00:01:23,165
And I felt that she trusted me
to capture the essence of her book

26
00:01:23,249 --> 00:01:25,292
in my screenplay adaptation,

27
00:01:25,376 --> 00:01:28,212
because I felt that what the two
would eventually have in common

28
00:01:28,296 --> 00:01:32,424
was that they would both
be internal adventure stories.

29
00:01:32,509 --> 00:01:34,760
They would both be about resurrection,
in a sense,

30
00:01:34,844 --> 00:01:36,970
and second chances in life.

31
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:40,432
It's true that this
is a pretty loose adaptation.

32
00:01:40,517 --> 00:01:43,560
Most of the characters in the movie
don't exist in the book,

33
00:01:43,645 --> 00:01:46,355
or are only suggested in the book.

34
00:01:47,398 --> 00:01:49,274
And yet, despite the additions,

35
00:01:49,359 --> 00:01:52,319
Frances Mayes ended up feeling
that the essence of her work

36
00:01:52,403 --> 00:01:56,532
was well translated to the screen,
and I was very happy about that.

37
00:01:57,075 --> 00:01:59,785
This first scene takes place
in a bookstore

38
00:01:59,869 --> 00:02:01,578
in North Beach of San Francisco.

39
00:02:01,663 --> 00:02:03,038
But in actual fact,

40
00:02:03,123 --> 00:02:07,751
we built this set on a sound stage
at Cinecitta Studios in Rome.

41
00:02:07,836 --> 00:02:08,836
For budgetary reasons,

42
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:11,421
it worked out better for us
to keep the same crew

43
00:02:11,506 --> 00:02:15,300
and to build all the San Francisco
interiors in Rome.

44
00:02:15,385 --> 00:02:17,719
It meant that I ended up
shooting in San Francisco,

45
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:19,805
my hometown, only one day.

46
00:02:20,723 --> 00:02:25,894
But I feel that we created some
authenticity on those stages in Rome.

47
00:02:26,896 --> 00:02:29,857
I think that bad reviews
should just be forgotten.

48
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:31,817
WELLS: lt was important
to me in this scene

49
00:02:31,901 --> 00:02:34,653
to show Diane Lane's character,
Frances,

50
00:02:34,737 --> 00:02:39,324
looking her very best, like a woman
in control, a happy woman.

51
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:42,494
And, ultimately, as we find out,
an unaware woman.

52
00:02:44,747 --> 00:02:48,125
I just find that ironic.

53
00:02:48,751 --> 00:02:50,878
Ironic? Why?

54
00:02:53,464 --> 00:02:54,506
Ask your husband.

55
00:02:57,927 --> 00:02:59,970
WELLS: One ofthe things
I looked forward to most

56
00:03:00,054 --> 00:03:01,180
before I started making the movie

57
00:03:01,264 --> 00:03:05,893
was the transition between
Diane's face here in this scene,

58
00:03:05,977 --> 00:03:09,688
and the way she looks
when we see her in the next scene.

59
00:03:10,940 --> 00:03:12,566
Here she is innocent.
She doesn't know yet.

60
00:03:13,234 --> 00:03:15,611
And then, when we find her
in the next scene,

61
00:03:15,695 --> 00:03:18,864
and we've leapt forward in time,
we quickly realize

62
00:03:18,948 --> 00:03:22,951
that she knows much, much more
than she knew before.

63
00:03:23,745 --> 00:03:27,789
The way she looks so ravaged in the
following scene is quite devastating.

64
00:03:27,957 --> 00:03:29,333
MAN: Frances.

65
00:03:29,834 --> 00:03:31,460
Frances?

66
00:03:33,796 --> 00:03:37,549
I've got some unfortunate news for you.

67
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:42,721
WELLS: l wanted Diane Lane
for this part,

68
00:03:42,805 --> 00:03:46,642
because I knew that I was going to be
making an overtly emotional movie.

69
00:03:46,726 --> 00:03:49,645
And that can be a tricky thing to do,
and a risky thing to do.

70
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:51,230
There are a lot of pitfalls.

71
00:03:51,314 --> 00:03:54,775
And its success lies entirely
on the actress.

72
00:03:54,984 --> 00:03:58,570
And I knew that Diane would have
the authenticity and the bravery

73
00:03:58,655 --> 00:04:01,448
in front of the camera
to carry that off for me.

74
00:04:02,992 --> 00:04:06,995
And also that I could frame this serious
subject matter in a humorous way,

75
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:09,539
and that with Diane in the main part,

76
00:04:09,749 --> 00:04:13,877
the audience would never lose touch
with the core pain of the character.

77
00:04:13,962 --> 00:04:16,505
That no matter how light I got later on,

78
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:18,799
Diane would always ground the movie
with her performance.

79
00:04:18,883 --> 00:04:22,469
We would never lose touch
with what we were really dealing with.

80
00:04:22,553 --> 00:04:24,012
$200,000.

81
00:04:24,806 --> 00:04:28,016
-I don't have that kind of money.
-Unfortunately, you do.

82
00:04:29,769 --> 00:04:31,103
The house?

83
00:04:31,354 --> 00:04:33,438
WELLS: This is Jeffrey Tambor
playing the attorney.

84
00:04:34,148 --> 00:04:37,109
It's a tricky thing
trying to cast a really good actor

85
00:04:37,193 --> 00:04:38,610
in a part that only plays one day.

86
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:43,448
Particularly when they have to fly
halfway across the world to do the role.

87
00:04:43,533 --> 00:04:45,075
And I was really happy to get Jeffrey,

88
00:04:45,159 --> 00:04:48,870
because I admire the way he layers his
performances with so much nuance.

89
00:04:49,872 --> 00:04:52,958
He was very impressed with Diane
the day we filmed this scene,

90
00:04:53,042 --> 00:04:55,836
and thought that we should just
keep him as an off-camera voice,

91
00:04:55,920 --> 00:04:59,339
because why cut away from Diane
when she was being so riveting?

92
00:05:00,800 --> 00:05:02,592
And if you let him have it, well,

93
00:05:02,677 --> 00:05:07,097
you could end up
with a lot of money in your pocket.

94
00:05:07,181 --> 00:05:09,516
I understand he wants it pretty badly.

95
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:12,728
Sorry. This is so surreal.

96
00:05:12,812 --> 00:05:15,856
WELLS: Diane came in completely
prepared to film this scene.

97
00:05:15,940 --> 00:05:16,982
She walked onto the set

98
00:05:17,066 --> 00:05:20,444
looking pretty much
exactly as you see her here.

99
00:05:20,528 --> 00:05:22,654
And we only filmed two takes.

100
00:05:22,739 --> 00:05:25,240
This is take one
that I am using in the movie.

101
00:05:26,159 --> 00:05:29,453
My experience with Diane is that she
rarely needed more than three takes

102
00:05:29,537 --> 00:05:31,330
to achieve what we were looking for.

103
00:05:31,748 --> 00:05:34,207
It's near the right schools.

104
00:05:36,127 --> 00:05:39,463
Schools. She's...

105
00:05:44,761 --> 00:05:46,470
Wow.

106
00:05:48,097 --> 00:05:50,640
You're gonna get over this.

107
00:05:52,060 --> 00:05:54,061
WELLS: Here when
Jeffrey Tambor says to her,

108
00:05:54,145 --> 00:05:55,354
"You will get over this, Frances.

109
00:05:55,438 --> 00:05:57,981
"You will.
Some day you will be happy again."

110
00:05:59,275 --> 00:06:00,859
That's the kickoff for the movie,

111
00:06:00,943 --> 00:06:02,235
because we look at that face
and we think,

112
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:04,988
"No, she will never be happy again."

113
00:06:06,032 --> 00:06:09,242
And that, for me,
established the tension

114
00:06:09,327 --> 00:06:13,789
and defined the road
that the movie was going to take.

115
00:06:13,873 --> 00:06:15,832
He says,
"Someday you will be happy again."

116
00:06:15,917 --> 00:06:18,418
We don't believe it.
But we are about to see it happen.

117
00:06:23,466 --> 00:06:28,095
I thought it was important to show
the house that Frances lived in,

118
00:06:28,179 --> 00:06:31,973
even though we never see
the ex-husband.

119
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:34,142
I felt that he would have
more creepy power

120
00:06:34,227 --> 00:06:38,188
if I didn't identify him
with a particular actor playing the part.

121
00:06:38,272 --> 00:06:40,774
I thought leaving him as a sinister ghost

122
00:06:40,858 --> 00:06:44,486
was more powerful for the movie.

123
00:06:44,570 --> 00:06:47,906
But I still wanted to see
what she was leaving behind.

124
00:06:47,990 --> 00:06:49,950
Actually, that painting
that we placed behind her,

125
00:06:50,034 --> 00:06:51,618
you can't really see the whole thing,

126
00:06:51,702 --> 00:06:54,204
but it's a black specter
lurking behind her shoulder,

127
00:06:54,288 --> 00:06:56,123
and I thought that
that represented the husband

128
00:06:56,207 --> 00:06:58,083
on some subconscious way

129
00:06:58,167 --> 00:07:01,253
that only l will ever (LAUGHlNG)
know about.

130
00:07:07,844 --> 00:07:09,428
This action that Diane takes here

131
00:07:09,512 --> 00:07:12,013
is something we came up
with in rehearsal that day.

132
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:15,267
And later I realized that the gesture
of taking flowers out of a vase

133
00:07:15,351 --> 00:07:17,060
is repeated several times in the movie

134
00:07:17,145 --> 00:07:19,980
by the old man who attends the shrine
outside Bramasole.

135
00:07:21,065 --> 00:07:24,651
Here in this scene, it's a sort
of harbinger of things to come.

136
00:07:27,405 --> 00:07:30,699
We always refer to this location
as the divorce hotel.

137
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:34,828
That's Jack Kehler, a terrific
character actor, playing the landlord.

138
00:07:35,163 --> 00:07:37,956
The guy crying through the wall
is Matthew Labyorteaux.

139
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:40,292
He auditioned for me
over the phone in Los Angeles.

140
00:07:40,376 --> 00:07:43,670
He called me up one evening
and sobbed over the telephone for me,

141
00:07:43,754 --> 00:07:45,964
so I could get a feel
for what he would do

142
00:07:46,048 --> 00:07:48,884
when we brought him
onto the looping stage.

143
00:07:49,343 --> 00:07:51,511
Later I found out
that he had played Albert Ingalls

144
00:07:51,596 --> 00:07:53,680
on Little House on the Prairie.

145
00:07:53,764 --> 00:07:57,350
It's pretty amazing who you have
access to in Los Angeles.

146
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:00,395
-What do you do?
-I'm a writer.

147
00:08:01,105 --> 00:08:04,858
So you can help the others
with their suicide notes.

148
00:08:04,942 --> 00:08:07,903
Ah, you're one of those funny landlords.

149
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:10,405
Not really.

150
00:08:11,741 --> 00:08:13,992
Well, here's your keys.

151
00:08:14,785 --> 00:08:16,912
Have a good stay.

152
00:08:17,914 --> 00:08:19,915
Thanks.

153
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:23,168
WELLS: We designed this room
to feel like purgatory,

154
00:08:23,252 --> 00:08:25,670
a sort of way station for Frances.

155
00:08:25,755 --> 00:08:29,508
And I had it filled with golf posters
to make it especially depressing.

156
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:33,678
Home.

157
00:08:38,768 --> 00:08:40,977
WELLS: This San Francisco
restaurant interior

158
00:08:41,062 --> 00:08:45,357
was actually shot inside a store
called Tod in the center of Rome.

159
00:08:47,235 --> 00:08:50,820
Sandra Oh is the actress that plays
Frances' best friend, Patti.

160
00:08:50,905 --> 00:08:53,031
I never considered another actress
for the part.

161
00:08:53,115 --> 00:08:56,159
I knew Sandra
from my first film, Guinevere,

162
00:08:56,244 --> 00:08:59,663
and I knew that she had
a unique, inimitable presence.

163
00:08:59,747 --> 00:09:03,500
It's hard to express
what makes Sandra so special,

164
00:09:03,584 --> 00:09:05,001
but it has something to do

165
00:09:05,086 --> 00:09:09,464
with how she manages to project
gravity and levity simultaneously.

166
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:14,386
I decided to include
a lesbian couple in the movie,

167
00:09:14,470 --> 00:09:18,598
because as I was working
on my theme about heartbreak,

168
00:09:18,683 --> 00:09:20,767
I knew that if I didn't include
a lesbian couple,

169
00:09:20,851 --> 00:09:24,145
I would only be featuring men
breaking women's hearts,

170
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:27,148
and I think heartbreak
is an equal opportunity killer.

171
00:09:30,945 --> 00:09:34,239
-It changes our plans a little bit.
-Well, of course.

172
00:09:34,323 --> 00:09:37,492
We were about to take a 1 0-day tour
to romantic Tuscany,

173
00:09:37,827 --> 00:09:40,537
but I don't want Patti flying
during her first trimester.

174
00:09:40,621 --> 00:09:41,746
Small sacrifice.

175
00:09:41,831 --> 00:09:44,499
WELLS: When l watch this scene
I am reminded of many happy hours

176
00:09:44,584 --> 00:09:48,211
in front of the Avid
with my editor, Andy Marcus.

177
00:09:48,296 --> 00:09:51,548
A scene like this one, essentially,
it's three talking heads,

178
00:09:51,632 --> 00:09:54,134
can be death without timing.

179
00:09:54,218 --> 00:09:57,053
Andy always brought crispness
to the scenes,

180
00:09:57,138 --> 00:10:00,015
and I think this kind of character-based
editing can be just as challenging

181
00:10:00,099 --> 00:10:04,102
as cutting action scenes
that entail thousands of feet of footage.

182
00:10:04,854 --> 00:10:06,605
No. Like that.

183
00:10:06,689 --> 00:10:10,483
-That's your depression speaking.
-Well, it doesn't speak Italian.

184
00:10:10,568 --> 00:10:13,778
It speaks a little high-school French.
Besides, I'm not depressed anymore.

185
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:17,115
Then what are you still doing living
at Camp Divorce with all those losers?

186
00:10:17,199 --> 00:10:20,076
-Be nice. Those are my people.
-That's not a place you live.

187
00:10:20,244 --> 00:10:22,245
Guys, come on.

188
00:10:23,039 --> 00:10:24,789
Thank you so much.

189
00:10:24,874 --> 00:10:26,708
There is no way that I can go

190
00:10:26,792 --> 00:10:28,668
on a romantic tour of Tuscany
right now, okay?

191
00:10:28,753 --> 00:10:32,130
-I mean, I'm not ready to meet anyone.
-Oh, you won't. That we can assure you.

192
00:10:32,214 --> 00:10:33,214
Oh?

193
00:10:35,176 --> 00:10:37,844
-It's a gay tour of romantic Tuscany.
-Oh.

194
00:10:37,928 --> 00:10:40,680
So it would be very relaxing for you.

195
00:10:40,765 --> 00:10:44,934
Mostly couples, no one would be there
to hit on you or check you out,

196
00:10:45,019 --> 00:10:48,521
and you could just concentrate
and listen to your own inner voice.

197
00:10:48,606 --> 00:10:53,401
My inner voice.
My inner voice that would be saying,

198
00:10:53,486 --> 00:10:55,820
"What the fuck am I doing
on a gay tour of Tuscany?"

199
00:10:55,905 --> 00:10:59,074
Frances, it's Italy. Italy.

200
00:10:59,158 --> 00:11:01,701
Plus, you could use it
as a time to start writing.

201
00:11:02,787 --> 00:11:06,498
Well, I'm busy.
I have to review all those books, Patti.

202
00:11:06,582 --> 00:11:08,041
Instead of working on your own book.

203
00:11:09,794 --> 00:11:11,252
WELLS: Post-production on this film,

204
00:11:11,337 --> 00:11:15,382
meaning the picture and sound editing,
was a nonstop pleasure, really,

205
00:11:15,466 --> 00:11:19,427
but production, the actual shoot in Italy
was a much more challenging story.

206
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:23,264
People have asked me,
with a lot of envy,

207
00:11:23,349 --> 00:11:25,809
what it was like to spend
four months working in Italy.

208
00:11:25,893 --> 00:11:29,562
But that's just the thing. We were
working. It wasn't exactly a vacation.

209
00:11:30,272 --> 00:11:33,692
And there were cultural differences
that we all had to adjust to.

210
00:11:33,776 --> 00:11:37,112
American movie crews
work a guaranteed 12 hours,

211
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:40,615
and frequently 14 hours,
and they'll work up to 17 hours,

212
00:11:40,700 --> 00:11:44,035
if you make a deal with them
and they want the overtime.

213
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:46,538
Whereas, ltalian crews
work a 10-hour day

214
00:11:46,622 --> 00:11:48,832
and one to two hours of that is lunch,

215
00:11:48,916 --> 00:11:51,209
and they're really not interested
in earning the overtime.

216
00:11:51,293 --> 00:11:53,670
They want to go home,
they want to watch the soccer game,

217
00:11:53,754 --> 00:11:56,131
they want to participate in their
(CHUCKLING) real lives.

218
00:11:56,215 --> 00:11:58,466
Which is easy to understand
from their point of view,

219
00:11:58,551 --> 00:12:01,803
but difficult for a director
who is trying to accomplish a lot

220
00:12:01,887 --> 00:12:03,847
and finish her scenes.

221
00:12:05,182 --> 00:12:08,727
When I finally shot my one day
in San Francisco,

222
00:12:08,811 --> 00:12:13,398
the day that you see here,
I shot a 17-hour day.

223
00:12:13,482 --> 00:12:15,692
And it was the longest work day
that we'd ever had on the movie,

224
00:12:15,818 --> 00:12:18,611
because we were working
with an American crew.

225
00:12:22,158 --> 00:12:24,784
(SOBBING NEXT DOOR)

226
00:12:31,417 --> 00:12:32,834
Hey!

227
00:12:32,918 --> 00:12:35,670
-Sorry. Sorry.
-It's okay.

228
00:12:36,839 --> 00:12:40,175
-You wanna come over?
-No!

229
00:12:40,342 --> 00:12:42,844
(QUIETER SOBBING)

230
00:12:43,637 --> 00:12:45,847
Maybe later.

231
00:12:46,682 --> 00:12:48,892
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

232
00:12:51,228 --> 00:12:53,480
"Maybe later." Oh...

233
00:13:00,362 --> 00:13:03,615
WELLS: The composer on this movie
is Christophe Beck,

234
00:13:03,699 --> 00:13:05,116
and l knew l wanted to work with him,

235
00:13:05,201 --> 00:13:07,619
because we'd worked together
so successfully

236
00:13:07,703 --> 00:13:09,329
on Guinevere, my first film.

237
00:13:09,413 --> 00:13:11,247
And I'd enjoyed my time
with Chris so much

238
00:13:11,332 --> 00:13:13,875
that I was looking forward
to doing it again.

239
00:13:15,377 --> 00:13:18,254
We discussed what we wanted
the music to sound like for this film.

240
00:13:18,339 --> 00:13:23,301
We divided it into three strands
that would become a single braid.

241
00:13:23,385 --> 00:13:25,887
One sound would be
a fresh and modern sound,

242
00:13:25,971 --> 00:13:30,350
like the one you hear right here,
that would be Frances' music.

243
00:13:30,434 --> 00:13:34,145
Another sound for the movie
would be a more romantic, comedic,

244
00:13:34,230 --> 00:13:36,147
classically Italian sound.

245
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:39,567
And the last thread
that we wanted to develop

246
00:13:39,652 --> 00:13:42,487
would reference the great composer,
Nino Rota,

247
00:13:42,571 --> 00:13:44,364
who scored all of Fellini's films.

248
00:13:44,490 --> 00:13:46,825
-Now, Frances is straight...
-Aw...

249
00:13:46,909 --> 00:13:49,202
...and she just survived
a terrible divorce,

250
00:13:49,286 --> 00:13:52,413
and according to her friend Patti,
she really needs our support.

251
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:57,252
So, Frances, why don't you stand up
and let everyone say hello?

252
00:13:57,336 --> 00:13:59,879
Come on, Frances, come on.

253
00:14:01,632 --> 00:14:02,674
Hi.

254
00:14:02,758 --> 00:14:04,843
Screw the bastard, Frances!
Have some fun!

255
00:14:05,719 --> 00:14:09,514
WELLS: l didn't know that it was going
to rain on this day in Florence.

256
00:14:09,598 --> 00:14:12,058
I was making a movie
called Under the Tuscan Sun,

257
00:14:12,142 --> 00:14:15,645
and the weather was rather distressing.

258
00:14:15,729 --> 00:14:19,315
But we decided to make the most of it,
and we got a bunch of red umbrellas.

259
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:21,192
And it ended up having
kind of a comedic feeling

260
00:14:21,277 --> 00:14:24,279
that the weather was so bad
and stayed bad.

261
00:14:25,781 --> 00:14:31,703
This begins the saga of our horrible
historically rainy fall in Tuscany.

262
00:14:33,080 --> 00:14:35,373
When it wasn't raining, it was hazy,

263
00:14:35,457 --> 00:14:36,916
and for a while there I was certain

264
00:14:37,001 --> 00:14:40,461
I was going to be known as the woman
who made that ugly Tuscany movie.

265
00:14:40,671 --> 00:14:42,714
Yes, she can.

266
00:14:42,798 --> 00:14:45,174
Frances, a little more?

267
00:14:47,761 --> 00:14:49,554
Thank you.

268
00:14:49,638 --> 00:14:51,890
WELLS: These sunflowers l was
smart enough to get in pre-production

269
00:14:51,974 --> 00:14:54,475
before we started shooting in the fall.
We shot these in July.

270
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:56,060
I was stiII in the United States,

271
00:14:56,145 --> 00:14:58,730
and I'd just drawn some pictures
about what I wanted.

272
00:14:58,814 --> 00:15:01,399
And this beautiful shot
we went back to get in May

273
00:15:01,483 --> 00:15:02,650
after I convinced Disney

274
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:05,653
that I was the woman
making the ugly Tuscany movie.

275
00:15:05,738 --> 00:15:10,074
We had some clear days in May
and some crystal clear horizons,

276
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:14,203
and I felt almost
religiously grateful for that.

277
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:18,416
The director of photography
that I chose to work with on this movie

278
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:21,586
is Geoffrey Simpson,
an Australian cinematographer,

279
00:15:21,670 --> 00:15:24,923
who had so many beautiful-looking
movies to his credit.

280
00:15:25,007 --> 00:15:27,342
We ended up
being great partners on this film,

281
00:15:27,426 --> 00:15:30,511
and our approach to the movie
was to shoot in an almost touristic style

282
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:33,848
when Frances first gets to Italy
and is an outsider.

283
00:15:33,933 --> 00:15:36,184
And then, to use the camera
in a more organic way,

284
00:15:36,268 --> 00:15:39,812
when she has become quite literally
a part of the landscape.

285
00:15:43,108 --> 00:15:46,277
I was very lucky to have Lindsay
Duncan in the role of Katherine,

286
00:15:46,362 --> 00:15:47,612
and when I watch this scene

287
00:15:47,696 --> 00:15:49,614
I remember how concerned
I was that day

288
00:15:49,698 --> 00:15:53,242
about what the character would be
wearing the first time that we saw her.

289
00:15:53,327 --> 00:15:55,119
I wanted her to look outrageous,

290
00:15:55,204 --> 00:15:58,498
but not to seem so strange
that she took us out of the movie.

291
00:15:58,582 --> 00:16:00,041
I remember being tortured this day

292
00:16:00,125 --> 00:16:03,378
about whether or not she should
wear sunglasses and a hat,

293
00:16:03,462 --> 00:16:06,255
orjust sunglasses, orjust a hat.

294
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:09,300
Those first impressions are
so important.

295
00:16:09,385 --> 00:16:13,304
And I was very intent on creating
a believable character here,

296
00:16:13,389 --> 00:16:15,431
despite her outrageousness.

297
00:16:32,491 --> 00:16:34,450
We had two days
to shoot this sequence.

298
00:16:34,535 --> 00:16:37,787
The marketplace
and the upcoming postcard montage.

299
00:16:37,871 --> 00:16:40,289
But on the first day,
which started in full sun,

300
00:16:40,374 --> 00:16:43,418
a sleet storm moved in at noon,
and the wind was incredible.

301
00:16:43,502 --> 00:16:46,879
It knocked over all the lights
and tore the roofs off the food stalls.

302
00:16:46,964 --> 00:16:49,007
So we had to wrap
and still finish the scene

303
00:16:49,091 --> 00:16:51,634
in the amount of time originally allotted.

304
00:16:51,719 --> 00:16:53,011
And that meant that I had to give up

305
00:16:53,095 --> 00:16:55,930
on some fancy Steadicam stuff
that I had planned.

306
00:16:57,391 --> 00:16:58,433
I used to be.

307
00:17:00,144 --> 00:17:02,812
All right, well, have a go.

308
00:17:04,940 --> 00:17:07,942
-To my mom.
-Dear Mom.

309
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:10,028
WELLS: Having Frances
write the postcard

310
00:17:10,112 --> 00:17:14,991
was a way of getting into the text
of Frances Mayes' book.

311
00:17:15,075 --> 00:17:19,203
A lot of what you are hearing here
comes from Frances' book, verbatim.

312
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:22,874
And it also established the voice-over

313
00:17:22,958 --> 00:17:25,793
and allowed me to use it
later in the movie

314
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:28,504
in a way that would make us feel
that she was actually in the process

315
00:17:28,589 --> 00:17:30,840
of writing her book
when she was speaking.

316
00:17:32,009 --> 00:17:33,885
FRANCES: l eat a hot grape
from the market

317
00:17:33,969 --> 00:17:36,971
and the violet sweetness
breaks open in my mouth.

318
00:17:37,056 --> 00:17:39,348
It even smells purple.

319
00:17:39,433 --> 00:17:40,767
I wish I could stay here longer,

320
00:17:40,851 --> 00:17:43,186
but the bell of the campanile
reminds me of time.

321
00:17:43,270 --> 00:17:48,316
"Ding-dang-dong," the bell says,
instead of "Ding-dong."

322
00:17:48,400 --> 00:17:49,567
I wish you were here.

323
00:17:49,651 --> 00:17:50,860
Love...

324
00:17:51,653 --> 00:17:52,987
Rodney.

325
00:17:56,325 --> 00:17:58,159
Thanks.

326
00:18:03,040 --> 00:18:06,918
"Even smells like purple"? My mom will
never believe that I wrote this.

327
00:18:07,002 --> 00:18:10,129
Keep it.
"'Ding-dang-dong,' goes the bell"!

328
00:18:11,381 --> 00:18:13,382
WELLS: That was Dan's addition,
Dan Bucatinsky,

329
00:18:13,467 --> 00:18:14,550
"Ding, dang, dong rang the bell."

330
00:18:15,010 --> 00:18:17,095
He did that in the audition.
How can you resist that?

331
00:18:33,112 --> 00:18:34,362
"Bramasole."

332
00:18:34,446 --> 00:18:40,326
Bramasole. From "bramare,"
to yearn for, and "sole, " the sun.

333
00:18:40,828 --> 00:18:41,828
WELLS: Casting Lindsay Duncan

334
00:18:41,912 --> 00:18:43,996
was one of the best things
that happened on this movie.

335
00:18:44,081 --> 00:18:45,915
She had just won the Tony
on Broadway

336
00:18:45,999 --> 00:18:47,750
forherrole in Private Lives.

337
00:18:48,085 --> 00:18:52,421
And my casting director, Linda Lowy,
thought that I should meet Lindsay.

338
00:18:52,506 --> 00:18:57,051
We asked her to fly out to Los Angeles,
which she did on a Monday.

339
00:18:57,136 --> 00:18:59,220
She flew out
and flew back on the same day,

340
00:18:59,304 --> 00:19:02,056
because Mondays were dark
for her when she was on stage.

341
00:19:05,686 --> 00:19:08,354
I don't even really remember
her reading for the part.

342
00:19:08,438 --> 00:19:09,772
All I had to do was meet Lindsay

343
00:19:09,857 --> 00:19:12,108
and feel her energy to know
that she would be perfect.

344
00:19:25,164 --> 00:19:27,290
(CHATTER ON BUS)

345
00:19:37,926 --> 00:19:42,430
WELLS: Sheep are not very good
at taking direction.

346
00:19:42,556 --> 00:19:44,974
We spent an inordinate amount of time

347
00:19:45,058 --> 00:19:47,268
trying to get that bus to roll up
and see the sheep.

348
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:51,480
It's not the kind of day
that you really enjoy,

349
00:19:51,565 --> 00:19:53,524
because you know the sun
is going down

350
00:19:53,609 --> 00:19:55,401
and we were over schedule
at the time that we shot this,

351
00:19:55,485 --> 00:19:58,404
and had so many more places to go,
and more scenes to get.

352
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:12,627
Stop the bus.

353
00:20:13,378 --> 00:20:15,588
-Stop the bus.
-What?

354
00:20:21,011 --> 00:20:23,596
WELLS: So now we are
about to discover Bramasole.

355
00:20:23,680 --> 00:20:25,264
And finding this location

356
00:20:25,349 --> 00:20:28,726
was one of the toughest things
that we had to do in pre-production.

357
00:20:28,810 --> 00:20:30,436
We were going to be
shooting in this house

358
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:33,689
more hours
than in any other location in the movie,

359
00:20:33,774 --> 00:20:35,399
and we didn't have money
to build a set,

360
00:20:35,484 --> 00:20:38,361
so we needed to use
a practical location.

361
00:20:38,445 --> 00:20:42,406
And all the houses of that era
have small rooms and low ceilings,

362
00:20:42,491 --> 00:20:44,909
meaning there is no place
to hide the lights,

363
00:20:44,993 --> 00:20:47,536
and there's very little room
to maneuver.

364
00:20:48,789 --> 00:20:52,124
We chose this house because
the ceilings were a little bit higher,

365
00:20:52,209 --> 00:20:55,628
and it was fairly modest in scale,
which was important to me.

366
00:20:55,712 --> 00:20:57,755
I didn't want Frances buying a palazzo

367
00:20:57,839 --> 00:21:01,342
that none of us could ever imagine
coming close to.

368
00:21:03,136 --> 00:21:04,804
Stephen McCabe,
my production designer,

369
00:21:04,888 --> 00:21:07,223
really led the charge on this house.

370
00:21:07,307 --> 00:21:10,685
He knew that he could make it work,
and he made it very beautiful

371
00:21:10,769 --> 00:21:12,937
when it was completely unimpressive

372
00:21:13,021 --> 00:21:15,314
and actually off-putting
when I first saw it.

373
00:21:15,399 --> 00:21:16,440
(GASPS)

374
00:21:25,951 --> 00:21:28,202
WELLS: Obviously,
Frances fixing up the house

375
00:21:28,287 --> 00:21:31,455
is some kind of metaphor
for fixing up your life.

376
00:21:31,540 --> 00:21:32,581
It was important to me

377
00:21:32,666 --> 00:21:35,126
that we not make
a home-decorating movie, though.

378
00:21:35,836 --> 00:21:39,922
I really was less interested
in the remodeling aspects of the story

379
00:21:40,007 --> 00:21:43,467
than in anything else, and wanted
to spend very little time on it,

380
00:21:43,552 --> 00:21:47,930
and Steve and l agreed that she
would never really decorate her house.

381
00:21:48,015 --> 00:21:51,058
What we mostly did to indicate
an evolution on the set

382
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:54,812
was to change the way the rooms
were lit as time went on.

383
00:21:56,023 --> 00:21:59,233
Here in the scene when she first
comes, the curtains are half closed

384
00:21:59,318 --> 00:22:02,153
and you can't see the room
all that well,

385
00:22:02,237 --> 00:22:04,322
or have a real sense of the house yet,

386
00:22:04,406 --> 00:22:07,325
and as the story progresses and she
becomes more at home in Italy,

387
00:22:07,409 --> 00:22:11,162
we started to illuminate the rooms
more brightly and with more warmth.

388
00:22:12,622 --> 00:22:15,166
Why? It didn't get more valuable
in the last five minutes.

389
00:22:15,250 --> 00:22:17,668
The contessa feels
that she has asked too little,

390
00:22:17,753 --> 00:22:19,003
since you have agreed to buy it.

391
00:22:19,087 --> 00:22:21,172
That logic is absurd!

392
00:22:21,256 --> 00:22:22,882
Excuse me?

393
00:22:23,091 --> 00:22:25,259
What is the price?

394
00:22:26,511 --> 00:22:28,471
Are you bidding against us?

395
00:22:28,555 --> 00:22:31,140
Wait. We accept the new price.

396
00:22:31,266 --> 00:22:33,559
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

397
00:22:37,773 --> 00:22:39,815
WELLS: When l took on
the subject matter of this film,

398
00:22:39,900 --> 00:22:42,735
I was aware of the
not altogether positive opinion

399
00:22:42,819 --> 00:22:45,154
that many Europeans
have of Americans.

400
00:22:45,238 --> 00:22:48,407
And it was important to me
to represent that reality in the film,

401
00:22:48,492 --> 00:22:50,242
which is why I wrote these lines.

402
00:22:50,327 --> 00:22:53,454
You greedy Americans.
You think you are so entitled.

403
00:22:53,538 --> 00:22:57,500
-You ruin everything.
-A lot of us feel really badly about that.

404
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:01,170
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

405
00:23:01,296 --> 00:23:02,713
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

406
00:23:09,763 --> 00:23:12,139
Is it really double the price?

407
00:23:12,224 --> 00:23:15,643
-Il prezzo e veramente il doppio?
-Si.

408
00:23:16,186 --> 00:23:18,646
I can't pay double the price.

409
00:23:19,523 --> 00:23:22,733
But please tell the contessa that...

410
00:23:23,944 --> 00:23:26,987
Up until this point we haven't
really seen Vince Riotta's face,

411
00:23:27,072 --> 00:23:30,366
and this is the first time
we get a really good look at him.

412
00:23:30,450 --> 00:23:33,744
I wanted to get closer to him
as the scene progressed.

413
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:35,121
The shots were getting tighter

414
00:23:35,205 --> 00:23:39,125
from the first exchanges
in the earlier part of the scene.

415
00:23:39,584 --> 00:23:41,001
...men,

416
00:23:41,378 --> 00:23:43,003
chocolate.

417
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:50,177
WELLS: l like the way he watches her
in the scene.

418
00:23:50,262 --> 00:23:53,806
And when we first meet his character
and he is the real estate agent,

419
00:23:53,890 --> 00:23:55,307
I think the audience might dismiss him,

420
00:23:55,392 --> 00:23:56,934
not understanding
that he is about to be

421
00:23:57,018 --> 00:23:58,811
one of the most important characters
in the movie.

422
00:23:59,980 --> 00:24:02,022
But right here,
when you see the look in his eyes

423
00:24:02,107 --> 00:24:05,401
after she makes her admission,
it's a very powerful thing.

424
00:24:05,485 --> 00:24:09,989
We know that he sees her and that
he knows that she has a story.

425
00:24:14,077 --> 00:24:15,244
CONTESSA: No.

426
00:24:15,954 --> 00:24:17,037
No.

427
00:24:17,122 --> 00:24:21,125
I'm sorry, signora. The contessa's
family have lived here for generations,

428
00:24:21,251 --> 00:24:25,838
so understandably
it is very difficult for her to sell.

429
00:24:26,798 --> 00:24:28,966
Money is not the only issue.
She needs...

430
00:24:29,050 --> 00:24:31,719
Un segno di Dio. Un segno.

431
00:24:31,887 --> 00:24:36,140
A sign. I understand.
I believe in signs, too.

432
00:24:38,059 --> 00:24:40,144
Well, thank you. Thank you.

433
00:24:40,228 --> 00:24:41,270
Prego.

434
00:24:45,442 --> 00:24:48,277
WELLS: So this special effect
is accomplished by

435
00:24:48,361 --> 00:24:50,571
an Italian grip standing on a ladder

436
00:24:50,655 --> 00:24:53,532
with a broomstick that has a spoon
attached to the end of it

437
00:24:53,617 --> 00:24:58,162
in which is some yogurt
mixed with poppy seeds.

438
00:24:58,246 --> 00:25:01,165
It was important that the guy
with the best aim take the shot,

439
00:25:01,249 --> 00:25:03,542
so we wouldn't have to
wash Diane's hair and reset.

440
00:25:03,627 --> 00:25:06,086
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

441
00:25:06,296 --> 00:25:09,423
WOMAN: First we open an account
for you. Then you transfer the money.

442
00:25:09,508 --> 00:25:12,676
Here is the legal description of the land,
two oxen, two days.

443
00:25:12,761 --> 00:25:14,053
-I'm sorry?
-It's old-fashioned.

444
00:25:14,137 --> 00:25:15,930
The legal description.

445
00:25:16,014 --> 00:25:20,184
The land is measured by how long
it would take two oxen to plow it.

446
00:25:20,268 --> 00:25:21,769
That makes sense.

447
00:25:28,151 --> 00:25:33,030
WELLS: This actress here is Claudia
Gerini, and she is very famous in ltaly.

448
00:25:33,114 --> 00:25:37,409
She is always on television,
doing movies, hosting award shows.

449
00:25:37,494 --> 00:25:39,119
She is everywhere.

450
00:25:39,204 --> 00:25:43,290
And it was hard work for us to find
a day that she could spare the time

451
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:45,000
and come do this scene with us.

452
00:25:45,085 --> 00:25:48,629
But I wanted CIaudia,
because she is so sexy and beautiful,

453
00:25:48,713 --> 00:25:53,217
and represents the kind of Italian style
that I saw everywhere.

454
00:25:53,301 --> 00:25:56,095
Women who kind of lead
with their sexuality and power,

455
00:25:56,179 --> 00:25:57,680
Claudia has a lot of that.

456
00:25:59,766 --> 00:26:01,225
-Normale?
-Normale.

457
00:26:01,309 --> 00:26:02,601
Normale.

458
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:07,982
FRANCES: l have bought a house
in a foreign country.

459
00:26:08,650 --> 00:26:12,987
A house and the land
it takes two oxen two days to plow.

460
00:26:13,071 --> 00:26:16,490
Not having a plow or an ox,
I'll have to take their word on that.

461
00:26:16,992 --> 00:26:20,744
Buyer's remorse is a very common
affliction among new homeowners.

462
00:26:21,913 --> 00:26:25,583
WELLS: Something that doesn't
take place in Frances' book,

463
00:26:25,667 --> 00:26:27,626
but I thought was important
in the movie,

464
00:26:27,711 --> 00:26:30,379
was the sense of absolute terror
and regret

465
00:26:30,463 --> 00:26:33,173
about buying a 300-year-old house
in a foreign country,

466
00:26:33,258 --> 00:26:34,800
when you are all by yourself.

467
00:26:35,885 --> 00:26:39,930
FRANCES: l have inherited
10,000 empty wine bottles,

468
00:26:40,682 --> 00:26:42,308
one grape...

469
00:26:42,684 --> 00:26:47,938
WELLS: By far the hardest thing that
we got on film was the scorpion.

470
00:26:48,023 --> 00:26:52,276
Scorpions, like sheep,
are not very fond of taking direction.

471
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:56,196
We spent way too much time
watching scorpions crawl around.

472
00:26:56,281 --> 00:26:59,199
The scorpions were in Frances' book,
but, unfortunately,

473
00:26:59,284 --> 00:27:01,869
they were also in the house
that I was living in with my family

474
00:27:01,953 --> 00:27:03,370
while we were shooting.

475
00:27:03,580 --> 00:27:06,498
It became the norm to hear something
crunch under your foot

476
00:27:06,583 --> 00:27:09,293
in the middle of the night when
you were on your way to the bathroom.

477
00:27:09,377 --> 00:27:11,420
When l created Frances' character,

478
00:27:11,504 --> 00:27:13,964
I had it in my mind
that she was motherless.

479
00:27:14,049 --> 00:27:15,966
Which in most myths and fairy tales

480
00:27:16,051 --> 00:27:18,677
is actually a precondition
of becoming a heroine.

481
00:27:18,762 --> 00:27:20,220
To me this meant that she was ripe

482
00:27:20,305 --> 00:27:22,681
for a meaningful encounter
with the Madonna,

483
00:27:22,766 --> 00:27:25,351
the most powerful mother figure
of them all.

484
00:27:25,435 --> 00:27:26,560
PATTI: You did what?

485
00:27:27,437 --> 00:27:29,730
Frances bought a house in Tuscany!

486
00:27:29,856 --> 00:27:31,607
And you're gonna live there? Alone?

487
00:27:32,817 --> 00:27:36,820
WELLS: Patti's apartment is a set
that we built on the lot at Cinecitta.

488
00:27:36,905 --> 00:27:40,491
It turned out to be challenging
getting an American look in Italy.

489
00:27:40,575 --> 00:27:43,243
And we hired an American set dresser,
Nick Evans,

490
00:27:43,328 --> 00:27:45,663
to bring props from the United States.

491
00:27:45,747 --> 00:27:46,997
He went shopping at Target

492
00:27:47,082 --> 00:27:49,833
and brought 600 pounds of props
with him through customs.

493
00:27:50,460 --> 00:27:52,670
Well, I don't know.
You're the one who made the

494
00:27:52,754 --> 00:27:55,255
"empty-shell person
standing at the crossroads" speech.

495
00:27:55,465 --> 00:27:57,216
Oh, yeah, that was me.

496
00:27:57,300 --> 00:28:01,345
Okay. Wow!
So you bought a villa in Tuscany.

497
00:28:01,471 --> 00:28:04,473
-What's the place like?
-It needs a little work.

498
00:28:04,641 --> 00:28:06,183
Well, who's gonna do it?

499
00:28:06,267 --> 00:28:07,518
-I am.
-You are?

500
00:28:07,602 --> 00:28:11,105
-I never realized you were so handy.
-I can do things, you know.

501
00:28:11,189 --> 00:28:14,942
-Remember I fixed that drain.
-In your kitchen? No, that was me.

502
00:28:15,026 --> 00:28:17,152
I handed you the rubber thingy.

503
00:28:17,278 --> 00:28:20,030
The plunger? That was Tom.

504
00:28:20,949 --> 00:28:23,784
I can't believe it.
Why, why did you just say his name?

505
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:26,954
I'm sorry. I'm sorry, I forgot. I'm sorry.

506
00:28:27,122 --> 00:28:29,790
-I can make this work. You know?
-(RUMBLE OF THUNDER)

507
00:28:29,874 --> 00:28:33,585
Of course I didn't mean I was gonna
do all the work myself. I'm in Italy.

508
00:28:33,670 --> 00:28:36,213
I can hire the muscular descendants
of Roman gods...

509
00:28:36,297 --> 00:28:38,716
WELLS: l love Diane Lane
and Sandra Oh together.

510
00:28:38,800 --> 00:28:40,092
They had great chemistry

511
00:28:40,176 --> 00:28:43,262
and managed to project
a sense of history onto their friendship.

512
00:28:43,346 --> 00:28:45,889
I also love the way
they looked together physically.

513
00:28:45,974 --> 00:28:48,267
I think they were
exceptionally well matched.

514
00:28:48,351 --> 00:28:52,187
And not surprisingly, they remained
friends after the show.

515
00:28:52,272 --> 00:28:54,982
They always had fun on set together,
and it made it easy for them

516
00:28:55,066 --> 00:28:58,652
to come up with wonderful improvs
like this bit that Sandra added here.

517
00:28:59,738 --> 00:29:02,531
-Can you star-69 Italy?
-No.

518
00:29:02,824 --> 00:29:04,366
I'm gonna try.

519
00:29:07,454 --> 00:29:08,495
Hello?

520
00:29:12,667 --> 00:29:13,667
Okay.

521
00:29:16,129 --> 00:29:20,924
WELLS: This is the first day of shooting
here, and in some ways it was difficult,

522
00:29:21,009 --> 00:29:24,970
because we had effects,
we had wind, we had rain.

523
00:29:26,848 --> 00:29:29,433
We were actually
shooting during the day,

524
00:29:29,517 --> 00:29:32,978
which meant
that the location was tented.

525
00:29:33,062 --> 00:29:35,439
But it was good for Diane
to have something really active

526
00:29:35,523 --> 00:29:37,608
to do on day one.

527
00:29:37,692 --> 00:29:39,151
It's always hard to break the ice,

528
00:29:39,235 --> 00:29:41,111
and the physical demands of this scene

529
00:29:41,196 --> 00:29:43,697
helped Diane lose the inhibitions
of the first day.

530
00:29:46,534 --> 00:29:48,118
Diane really had to trust me

531
00:29:48,203 --> 00:29:50,454
that I was going to put some
scary lightning out those windows,

532
00:29:50,538 --> 00:29:55,626
because she was making the face of
someone who was completely terrified.

533
00:29:58,630 --> 00:30:00,297
This washing machine here,

534
00:30:00,381 --> 00:30:02,633
it's being moved along
by somebody pulling a string.

535
00:30:02,717 --> 00:30:05,719
And then, there is an air gun
in a hole underneath it

536
00:30:05,804 --> 00:30:07,930
that makes itjump up into the air.

537
00:30:08,014 --> 00:30:12,351
We shot it with two cameras
running at two different speeds.

538
00:30:12,435 --> 00:30:14,728
And, boy,
that was really exciting for me.

539
00:30:14,813 --> 00:30:17,439
Two cameras, you know.
Michael Bay, watch out.

540
00:30:18,066 --> 00:30:19,983
This owl was much better
at taking direction

541
00:30:20,068 --> 00:30:22,402
than the sheep or the scorpions.

542
00:30:23,488 --> 00:30:26,073
I think he has got a great spirit.

543
00:30:26,157 --> 00:30:29,910
And I like the way Diane
connects to other solitary animals.

544
00:30:29,994 --> 00:30:32,663
There was some kind of
method to my madness here.

545
00:30:32,747 --> 00:30:35,707
I feel like animals have a lot of pathos.

546
00:30:35,792 --> 00:30:39,002
And, obviously,
their greatest interest is in surviving.

547
00:30:39,087 --> 00:30:41,088
And Frances' survival instinct

548
00:30:41,172 --> 00:30:43,674
needs to kick in
at this time of her life also.

549
00:30:43,758 --> 00:30:46,343
And I felt that she had a kinship,

550
00:30:47,720 --> 00:30:49,680
a relationship to all the solitary animals
that show up in the movie.

551
00:30:54,018 --> 00:30:56,770
Vince Riotta, who plays Signor Martini,

552
00:30:57,647 --> 00:31:01,900
he was not a very well-known actor
when I was introduced to him

553
00:31:01,985 --> 00:31:05,320
by Beatrice Kruger,
my Italian casting director.

554
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:07,114
And in some ways, I think,

555
00:31:07,198 --> 00:31:09,825
the thing that scared me the most
on this movie was casting Vince.

556
00:31:09,909 --> 00:31:12,369
Because I didn't see
any other film on him.

557
00:31:12,453 --> 00:31:14,496
I only had his auditions to go on.

558
00:31:14,581 --> 00:31:21,545
And they were so perfectly pitched,
that I felt that I had to go with him.

559
00:31:27,302 --> 00:31:30,304
As a man, Vince is a young,

560
00:31:30,638 --> 00:31:35,517
kind of boyish guy
with a lot of youthful energy,

561
00:31:35,602 --> 00:31:40,522
and the restrained, reserved,
wizened man

562
00:31:40,607 --> 00:31:42,399
that he plays in this movie

563
00:31:42,483 --> 00:31:44,985
is entirely a performance
that he created.

564
00:31:46,404 --> 00:31:48,280
Oh, wonderful.

565
00:31:48,364 --> 00:31:52,910
You should have been an architect.
You have excellent taste.

566
00:31:52,994 --> 00:31:54,828
So, do you think it can be done?

567
00:31:55,622 --> 00:32:00,417
Heating pipes, a week.
The bathrooms, three days.

568
00:32:00,501 --> 00:32:03,503
Signora, give me the keys of this place

569
00:32:03,588 --> 00:32:06,882
and in one month I will give you back
the keys to your palace.

570
00:32:07,342 --> 00:32:08,842
Just...

571
00:32:10,762 --> 00:32:12,763
Just leave it to me.

572
00:32:13,222 --> 00:32:15,349
WELLS: ln this montage
with all the contractors

573
00:32:15,433 --> 00:32:17,184
I think about my casting directors

574
00:32:17,268 --> 00:32:19,269
and how important they were to me.

575
00:32:22,148 --> 00:32:24,650
A director can only choose actors

576
00:32:24,734 --> 00:32:27,778
from amongst the group
that the casting director brings.

577
00:32:27,862 --> 00:32:30,489
And those two were so creative

578
00:32:30,573 --> 00:32:33,158
and had such a good sense
of the script

579
00:32:33,242 --> 00:32:37,913
that I owe them a lot for finding
me actors like the ones that I did.

580
00:32:37,997 --> 00:32:42,960
This is Massimo Sarchielli right here
who'd been in a lot of Fellini's movies.

581
00:32:43,044 --> 00:32:45,879
I was thrilled to have an alumnus
of La Strada in my movie.

582
00:32:46,089 --> 00:32:50,050
Really? Oh.
You wanna see the rest of the house?

583
00:32:51,010 --> 00:32:52,844
Okay. Yes, yes.

584
00:32:57,433 --> 00:33:00,477
WELLS: Finding the three actors
who would play the Polish contractors

585
00:33:00,561 --> 00:33:03,146
was one of the biggest casting
challenges of the film.

586
00:33:03,231 --> 00:33:05,857
And finding a young,
beautifully fresh-faced actor

587
00:33:05,942 --> 00:33:08,902
who could speak Polish and handle
physically demanding scenes

588
00:33:08,987 --> 00:33:10,529
was especially difficult.

589
00:33:10,613 --> 00:33:14,408
Finding Pawel Szajda was like
finding a needle in a haystack.

590
00:33:14,909 --> 00:33:18,328
He is an American, actually,
born to Polish immigrant parents.

591
00:33:18,413 --> 00:33:21,164
And he sent us an audition tape
that he made all alone.

592
00:33:21,249 --> 00:33:23,000
He turned the camera on
and ran in front of it

593
00:33:23,084 --> 00:33:26,086
pretending to listen
to off-camera voices.

594
00:33:26,170 --> 00:33:28,630
It slayed me. This is his first film.

595
00:33:29,298 --> 00:33:32,259
-I am Pawel.
-Pawel. Nice to meet you.

596
00:33:34,178 --> 00:33:37,305
WELLS: That's Valentine Pelka.
He is British.

597
00:33:37,390 --> 00:33:41,309
And Sasa Vulicevic filled out
the third role.

598
00:33:41,394 --> 00:33:42,936
He is a Croatian living in Rome.

599
00:33:43,938 --> 00:33:46,440
-Zbignew.
-Zbignew.

600
00:33:47,191 --> 00:33:48,608
Frances.

601
00:33:51,612 --> 00:33:53,530
What do you think of Nino?

602
00:33:53,614 --> 00:33:57,409
I know his mother.
If he does a bad job, it's...

603
00:33:57,493 --> 00:33:59,119
Well, then...

604
00:34:00,538 --> 00:34:03,081
-Okay, yes.
-Okay, yes?

605
00:34:03,166 --> 00:34:04,624
Yes. Yes.

606
00:34:11,591 --> 00:34:13,759
Okay. Yes.

607
00:34:16,929 --> 00:34:19,347
WELLS: l tried to cast my Polish guys
from Poland.

608
00:34:19,432 --> 00:34:22,893
But the Italians were being slow
about approving work permits

609
00:34:22,977 --> 00:34:25,562
for Polish people to come
and work in Italy,

610
00:34:25,646 --> 00:34:27,230
which seemed very ironic to me,

611
00:34:27,315 --> 00:34:29,232
because, in a sense,
the Polish characters

612
00:34:29,317 --> 00:34:34,071
represent the plight of the immigrant
worker anywhere in the world.

613
00:34:34,155 --> 00:34:35,947
And here we were having
so many problems

614
00:34:36,032 --> 00:34:38,784
bringing people from Poland into Italy,

615
00:34:38,868 --> 00:34:40,535
and so many problems
getting work permits

616
00:34:40,620 --> 00:34:43,747
that I was forced to cast them
from other parts of the world.

617
00:34:46,209 --> 00:34:47,417
When l look at this scene,

618
00:34:47,502 --> 00:34:51,254
I remember all the plaster dust that all
the actors had to swallow that day.

619
00:34:51,339 --> 00:34:55,801
And considering that it was the first
working day for the Polish guys,

620
00:34:55,885 --> 00:34:59,971
(LAUGHING) l think they all considered
quitting after one day of work.

621
00:35:00,056 --> 00:35:05,936
The fact that I didn't have real
Polish actors to play the Polish workers

622
00:35:06,020 --> 00:35:08,647
meant that later on in post-production

623
00:35:08,731 --> 00:35:10,524
I had to add in some dialogue in Polish

624
00:35:10,608 --> 00:35:14,528
once we'd had time
to have Polish-speaking people

625
00:35:14,612 --> 00:35:16,279
teach us some words.

626
00:35:16,364 --> 00:35:21,952
And in Los Angeles one day a guy
came to fix my stove that had broken,

627
00:35:22,203 --> 00:35:25,247
and I started talking to him
and it turned out he was Polish.

628
00:35:25,331 --> 00:35:27,374
I asked him if he could
come into the studio

629
00:35:27,458 --> 00:35:30,752
and record some
temporary dialogue for us, and he did.

630
00:35:30,837 --> 00:35:33,839
l think he's got his SAG card now.
No more ovens for him.

631
00:35:35,633 --> 00:35:38,760
FRANCES: "Kurwa mac" means
"holy shit" in Polish.

632
00:35:38,845 --> 00:35:40,137
I learned that that day.

633
00:35:41,097 --> 00:35:43,557
The fact that I'm trying
to speak Polish in Italy

634
00:35:43,641 --> 00:35:46,768
is just one of the many surprises
around here.

635
00:35:51,983 --> 00:35:53,567
Is he a licensed electrician?

636
00:35:53,651 --> 00:35:55,610
WELLS: Valentine Pelka's
character, Jerzy,

637
00:35:55,695 --> 00:35:59,156
had the most mystery
of all the Polish workers.

638
00:35:59,991 --> 00:36:01,700
And in keeping with my idea

639
00:36:01,784 --> 00:36:04,161
that I would give everyone in the movie
a broken heart,

640
00:36:04,245 --> 00:36:07,205
I had decided that Jerzy
should wear a wedding ring,

641
00:36:07,290 --> 00:36:10,208
meaning he had had
to leave his beloved in Poland.

642
00:36:10,293 --> 00:36:11,960
Valentine is also married,

643
00:36:12,044 --> 00:36:14,671
and he was missing his wife and child
who were back home in England,

644
00:36:14,755 --> 00:36:16,298
and the concept worked for him.

645
00:36:22,263 --> 00:36:26,600
FRANCES: Every day l watch
for the old man with the flowers.

646
00:36:30,771 --> 00:36:34,024
WELLS: We called this character
"the old man with the flowers."

647
00:36:35,151 --> 00:36:37,277
FRANCES: Did he love someone here?

648
00:36:37,778 --> 00:36:40,697
WELLS: And one of my ltalian
colleagues on the movie

649
00:36:40,781 --> 00:36:42,949
suggested that we approach
Mario Monicelli

650
00:36:43,034 --> 00:36:45,619
to see if he would play the part.

651
00:36:46,162 --> 00:36:49,873
This was like getting
John Huston to act in your movie.

652
00:36:49,957 --> 00:36:53,710
Mario Monicelli is one of the most
famous directors in Italy alive today,

653
00:36:53,794 --> 00:36:57,047
and he's made over 60 films.
He is an icon.

654
00:36:57,173 --> 00:36:59,424
Having him in the movie
was a great honor.

655
00:37:00,927 --> 00:37:02,469
He was very nice to me that day.

656
00:37:02,553 --> 00:37:06,598
Only wanting to serve me
as best he could as an actor.

657
00:37:06,682 --> 00:37:08,266
He was enormously polite.

658
00:37:11,229 --> 00:37:14,606
FRANCES: Fortunately, there are some
things here you just can't do alone.

659
00:37:14,690 --> 00:37:16,983
It's my neighbor Placido
who's teaching me about olives.

660
00:37:17,068 --> 00:37:19,402
WELLS: When I look at these olives
I remember how much fear we had

661
00:37:19,487 --> 00:37:21,363
that by the time we would shoot
the olive grove,

662
00:37:21,447 --> 00:37:23,531
all the olives would be off the trees.

663
00:37:23,616 --> 00:37:26,243
We kept delaying and delaying
and delaying shooting this scene

664
00:37:26,327 --> 00:37:27,369
because of the bad weather.

665
00:37:27,453 --> 00:37:29,788
Every time it was scheduled
there would be a downpour that day,

666
00:37:29,872 --> 00:37:32,666
and we'd end up shooting
something in the house instead.

667
00:37:33,042 --> 00:37:35,252
The day that we finally went out there,

668
00:37:35,336 --> 00:37:39,798
there was no possibility
to postpone the shoot one more day,

669
00:37:39,882 --> 00:37:43,176
and so we went out there even
though it had rained in the morning,

670
00:37:43,261 --> 00:37:46,263
and, thank God, the rain stayed
in the clouds enough hours

671
00:37:46,347 --> 00:37:48,348
for us to get the scene.

672
00:37:49,433 --> 00:37:52,477
That actress is Giulia Steigerwalt,

673
00:37:52,561 --> 00:37:56,439
and I felt that she was
the perfect counterpart to Pawel.

674
00:37:57,149 --> 00:37:58,525
They are both very young actors.

675
00:37:58,609 --> 00:38:01,194
They were both 20 years old
when we shot the movie.

676
00:38:03,489 --> 00:38:06,408
They had some
genuine innocence to them.

677
00:38:06,492 --> 00:38:08,451
I don't really know how they'd feel
about my saying that,

678
00:38:08,536 --> 00:38:11,621
but there was something true
in each of them

679
00:38:11,706 --> 00:38:14,207
that made them perfect
to play the parts.

680
00:38:14,709 --> 00:38:16,876
They ended up
becoming extremely good friends.

681
00:38:23,217 --> 00:38:25,343
Francesca, are you busy tonight?

682
00:38:25,428 --> 00:38:26,720
No.

683
00:38:26,887 --> 00:38:29,472
Then come to dinner.
It's unhealthy to eat alone.

684
00:38:37,064 --> 00:38:41,318
WELLS: When that actor did that,
we all laughed so hard we hit the floor.

685
00:38:41,402 --> 00:38:44,696
His name is Marco Bonini
and he is a very popular actor in Italy.

686
00:38:48,034 --> 00:38:49,242
(SOBBING)

687
00:38:49,910 --> 00:38:52,620
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

688
00:38:52,747 --> 00:38:55,081
-Is she okay?
-Of course. She's fine.

689
00:38:55,333 --> 00:38:57,834
WELLS: The grandmotherhere
is EveIina Gori,

690
00:38:57,918 --> 00:39:00,211
and I was thrilled to work with her.

691
00:39:00,296 --> 00:39:04,507
She was already in her 90s
when she agreed to take this part,

692
00:39:04,592 --> 00:39:09,137
and she'd been an actress all of her life
and loved being in front of the camera.

693
00:39:12,767 --> 00:39:14,517
She had her own way of doing things.

694
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:17,562
She couldn't exactly
do lines as written,

695
00:39:17,646 --> 00:39:21,900
but she had such a significant
presence because of her age, I think,

696
00:39:21,984 --> 00:39:26,654
that I decided to rewrite the scenes
so that she could be in them

697
00:39:26,739 --> 00:39:29,240
even though she had limited
physical ability at the time.

698
00:39:30,659 --> 00:39:32,285
No.

699
00:39:33,037 --> 00:39:35,789
-Do you have one?
-One? Hah!

700
00:39:39,377 --> 00:39:40,794
(BEGINS SOBBING)

701
00:39:42,046 --> 00:39:44,172
I knew this would happen. Remember?

702
00:39:44,340 --> 00:39:47,759
Don't blame me.
I told him not to get her that computer.

703
00:39:47,843 --> 00:39:52,055
She got an email lover.
You see? From Ecuador!

704
00:39:52,139 --> 00:39:55,600
Finally, she had to tell him her age,
and now...

705
00:39:56,435 --> 00:39:58,061
WELLS: Evelina didn't speak
any English,

706
00:39:58,145 --> 00:40:00,730
and I didn't speak Italian,
the bane of my existence.

707
00:40:00,815 --> 00:40:03,858
So we were always talking
to each other through interpreters.

708
00:40:03,943 --> 00:40:06,027
And I don't know
that she really ever knew

709
00:40:06,112 --> 00:40:08,571
what the movie was about, or read
the whole script or anything like that,

710
00:40:08,656 --> 00:40:13,743
but she knew that it was her part
to care about love and defend love,

711
00:40:13,828 --> 00:40:16,913
and she felt very passionate
on that topic.

712
00:40:17,415 --> 00:40:21,042
So what you see from Evelina
comes from deep inside her.

713
00:40:22,169 --> 00:40:24,712
Come si dice in inglese? Celibe?

714
00:40:24,839 --> 00:40:26,297
Celibe...

715
00:40:27,591 --> 00:40:29,676
Celibate? Celibate?

716
00:40:32,763 --> 00:40:34,639
No. I mean...

717
00:40:35,433 --> 00:40:40,145
Well, actually, I have to admit
it has been a while.

718
00:40:41,647 --> 00:40:43,648
Celibe in Italian means single.

719
00:40:44,191 --> 00:40:46,067
He's not asking when you last had sex,

720
00:40:46,152 --> 00:40:47,569
he's asking whether
or not you're married.

721
00:40:49,697 --> 00:40:50,989
Thank you.

722
00:40:51,115 --> 00:40:53,533
WELLS: l love Diane's
vulnerability here.

723
00:40:53,993 --> 00:40:55,535
I always find, as a screenwriter,

724
00:40:55,703 --> 00:40:57,787
that it's important
to kick around your protagonist

725
00:40:57,872 --> 00:41:00,707
and drag them through the mud
as much as possible.

726
00:41:03,210 --> 00:41:06,087
I'm always looking for ways
to beat up my characters.

727
00:41:06,422 --> 00:41:08,131
Oh, my God.

728
00:41:08,257 --> 00:41:09,799
FRANCES: I feel like such an idiot.

729
00:41:09,884 --> 00:41:13,845
Don't. Flirting's a ritual in Italy.
Just enjoy it.

730
00:41:13,929 --> 00:41:16,389
Taste this. It's gorgeous.

731
00:41:17,391 --> 00:41:18,433
Mm.

732
00:41:20,186 --> 00:41:22,061
-How do you do it?
-Do what?

733
00:41:22,897 --> 00:41:24,147
This.

734
00:41:24,231 --> 00:41:25,482
WELLS: This character Katherine

735
00:41:25,566 --> 00:41:28,985
is quite obviously in the spirit
of Fellini's women.

736
00:41:29,069 --> 00:41:30,653
The costume designer, Nicoletta,

737
00:41:30,738 --> 00:41:35,158
dressed her in replica costumes
from some of Fellini's films.

738
00:41:35,242 --> 00:41:40,038
And this fantastic hat ended up flying
into the fountain the night that we shot.

739
00:41:40,122 --> 00:41:41,664
As you can see, it's very windy

740
00:41:41,749 --> 00:41:44,626
and it wasn't pinned
onto her head well enough.

741
00:41:46,003 --> 00:41:48,880
I will never forget how when
the hat flew off into the fountain

742
00:41:48,964 --> 00:41:52,175
that Nicoletta dove into the fountain
at 3:00 in the morning

743
00:41:52,259 --> 00:41:55,178
on a freezing night to fish it out of there.

744
00:41:55,763 --> 00:41:57,347
And then,
there was some touch and go time

745
00:41:57,431 --> 00:42:00,433
with the blow dryer in the cafe
that you see in the background,

746
00:42:00,518 --> 00:42:04,145
while we hoped that the hat
could be restored to its former glory

747
00:42:04,230 --> 00:42:06,523
and could still make it
through the scene.

748
00:42:07,858 --> 00:42:10,944
He wasn't just a great director,
he gave great advice.

749
00:42:11,195 --> 00:42:12,570
I'm listening.

750
00:42:13,405 --> 00:42:18,785
Fefe said you have to live spherically,
in many directions.

751
00:42:19,453 --> 00:42:21,996
WELLS: Katherine does espouse
Fellini's philosophies.

752
00:42:22,081 --> 00:42:26,125
The things that she says
are actual quotes from Fellini.

753
00:42:27,503 --> 00:42:30,129
And I felt that they had thematic value
for the movie.

754
00:42:31,257 --> 00:42:35,093
FRANCES: So now l was getting
posthumous advice from Il Maestro.

755
00:42:35,177 --> 00:42:37,303
And I tried to follow it by pulling ivy

756
00:42:37,388 --> 00:42:39,639
spherically
and with childish enthusiasm.

757
00:42:40,432 --> 00:42:42,517
WELLS: A lot ofpeople
are terrified of snakes.

758
00:42:42,601 --> 00:42:44,936
I am not one of them
and neither is Diane.

759
00:42:45,020 --> 00:42:47,105
She was perfectly happy
to help us get this shot

760
00:42:47,189 --> 00:42:50,608
and grab the snake and try and
direct its head back over the window.

761
00:42:55,239 --> 00:42:56,406
Niente qui.

762
00:43:00,077 --> 00:43:01,828
Niente. Not here.

763
00:43:09,503 --> 00:43:14,173
WELLS: This scene we always
referred to as the train scene.

764
00:43:14,258 --> 00:43:17,427
I always thought of it
as the center of the movie.

765
00:43:23,851 --> 00:43:25,143
(GASPS)

766
00:43:25,686 --> 00:43:27,895
No, it's a joke.

767
00:43:29,023 --> 00:43:31,441
WELLS: We all looked forward
to the shooting of this scene.

768
00:43:31,525 --> 00:43:34,736
We rehearsed it mostly in blocking.

769
00:43:35,696 --> 00:43:39,907
I brought Vince and Diane
up to the room one day during lunch,

770
00:43:39,992 --> 00:43:42,076
and we kind of walked
through the paces of it.

771
00:43:42,870 --> 00:43:46,039
We had spent a day,
the three of us, previously,

772
00:43:46,123 --> 00:43:48,291
reading over the scenes
of the entire movie.

773
00:43:48,375 --> 00:43:51,252
That was all the time we ever spent
rehearsing was that one day.

774
00:43:51,337 --> 00:43:53,755
Diane had one day with each actor.

775
00:43:54,840 --> 00:43:56,883
I'm sorry.

776
00:43:58,969 --> 00:44:03,264
WELLS: But poor Vince had so
anticipated shooting this scene

777
00:44:03,349 --> 00:44:06,351
and had had to do it for me
so many times in auditions

778
00:44:06,435 --> 00:44:09,646
that by the time we finally shot it,
he must've,

779
00:44:09,730 --> 00:44:12,607
oh, l don't know,
done it 20 times already.

780
00:44:22,284 --> 00:44:24,827
It was important to me
that the character of Frances

781
00:44:24,912 --> 00:44:27,789
talk about her divorce again
in this scene.

782
00:44:27,873 --> 00:44:29,874
We hadn't really heard about it
for a long time.

783
00:44:29,958 --> 00:44:32,335
Not since her character
left San Francisco.

784
00:44:32,419 --> 00:44:35,672
And I thought maybe we felt
that it was behind her.

785
00:44:36,507 --> 00:44:38,675
I like the way it comes up here
right out of the blue

786
00:44:38,759 --> 00:44:41,469
to show that this is still something
that she is really grappling with

787
00:44:41,553 --> 00:44:44,263
and that she is identifying herself by.

788
00:44:44,765 --> 00:44:47,892
You shouldn't have to wake up
day after day after something like that,

789
00:44:47,976 --> 00:44:51,521
trying to understand
how in the world you didn't know.

790
00:44:53,691 --> 00:44:57,360
WELLS: Stephen McCabe brought
that little fireplace in for me.

791
00:44:57,444 --> 00:45:00,196
l wanted to give Signor Martini
something to do.

792
00:45:00,280 --> 00:45:01,698
A way to hide from her

793
00:45:01,782 --> 00:45:05,201
while she is telling him
all these terribly personal things.

794
00:45:05,285 --> 00:45:09,664
I felt that his character would be
both embarrassed by the intimacy,

795
00:45:09,748 --> 00:45:11,999
and also kind of thrilled by it.

796
00:45:12,918 --> 00:45:16,212
And it was nice for Vince
to be able to stay busy with something

797
00:45:16,296 --> 00:45:18,589
while he got through the scene.

798
00:45:21,301 --> 00:45:22,885
The fireplace works for the scene,

799
00:45:22,970 --> 00:45:27,056
but when I see it I am reminded
of how poorly it actually functioned,

800
00:45:27,141 --> 00:45:31,269
spewing smoke into the room that
choked the actors every 45 seconds.

801
00:45:31,353 --> 00:45:34,564
Suffice to say,
that's not how it's supposed to work.

802
00:45:34,648 --> 00:45:36,774
We had to stop constantly
to air out the room,

803
00:45:36,859 --> 00:45:41,279
which was hard for them to do
in an emotional scene like this one.

804
00:45:44,825 --> 00:45:47,160
Why did you do it, then?

805
00:45:53,125 --> 00:45:56,002
WELLS: The story that Signor Martini
tells Frances in this scene

806
00:45:56,086 --> 00:45:58,755
about the train tracks built
across the Semmering Pass

807
00:45:58,839 --> 00:46:02,717
is a true story related to me
by my Austrian father.

808
00:46:02,801 --> 00:46:04,469
And if I'd never heard that story,

809
00:46:04,553 --> 00:46:06,596
I don't know if I would've
ever written this movie.

810
00:46:06,680 --> 00:46:10,266
It was the springboard and, actually,
the reason for the film.

811
00:46:11,393 --> 00:46:12,602
Between Austria and Italy

812
00:46:12,686 --> 00:46:16,731
there is a section of the Alps
called the Semmering.

813
00:46:16,815 --> 00:46:20,443
It is an impossibly steep,
very high part of the mountains.

814
00:46:20,527 --> 00:46:24,864
They built a train track over these Alps
to connect Vienna and Venice.

815
00:46:24,948 --> 00:46:26,616
They built these tracks

816
00:46:26,700 --> 00:46:31,162
even before there was a train in
existence that could make the trip.

817
00:46:32,581 --> 00:46:36,959
They built it because they knew
someday the train would come.

818
00:46:40,172 --> 00:46:42,381
WELLS: I love the transition
on Diane's face right here

819
00:46:42,466 --> 00:46:45,718
when she goes from just being touched
that he told her the story

820
00:46:45,803 --> 00:46:48,513
into thinking
that maybe she needs him.

821
00:46:52,100 --> 00:46:54,560
And I love the way
he registers that look.

822
00:46:54,645 --> 00:46:57,563
They had fantastic
unspoken communication.

823
00:46:59,274 --> 00:47:03,069
I think your snake
has gone for the evening.

824
00:47:03,153 --> 00:47:05,571
Yes, I think you're right.

825
00:47:11,912 --> 00:47:13,412
WELLS: There is a lot of
beautiful tension

826
00:47:13,497 --> 00:47:14,747
between these two in this scene,

827
00:47:14,832 --> 00:47:17,333
and one of my favorite things
that we were able to do in the movie

828
00:47:17,417 --> 00:47:20,044
is show that sometimes men
and women can be friends

829
00:47:20,128 --> 00:47:23,130
without crossing any taboo lines

830
00:47:23,215 --> 00:47:25,508
and staying true
to their other commitments,

831
00:47:25,592 --> 00:47:28,511
despite some great attraction
that they might have for each other.

832
00:47:28,929 --> 00:47:32,598
I liked being able to portray
that kind of friendship in this movie.

833
00:47:38,981 --> 00:47:40,273
Buona notte, signora.

834
00:47:41,191 --> 00:47:44,443
Buona notte, Signor Martini.
E grazie per tutto.

835
00:47:45,612 --> 00:47:46,988
Prego.

836
00:47:55,455 --> 00:47:56,581
(SIGHS)

837
00:47:58,250 --> 00:48:01,669
FRANCES: A train track through
the Alps before there was a train.

838
00:48:01,753 --> 00:48:03,963
Signor Martini wants me to have faith,

839
00:48:04,047 --> 00:48:05,298
something I've never been good at...

840
00:48:06,258 --> 00:48:08,926
WELLS: This image is called
the Running Madonna.

841
00:48:09,011 --> 00:48:11,554
When I reached Italy,
my assistant Edoardo Petti,

842
00:48:11,638 --> 00:48:15,224
who later became
an associate producer on the movie,

843
00:48:15,309 --> 00:48:17,476
he told me about this tradition

844
00:48:17,561 --> 00:48:19,812
that existed elsewhere in Italy,
not in Tuscany,

845
00:48:19,897 --> 00:48:21,647
but we borrowed it for the film.

846
00:48:25,736 --> 00:48:28,195
I included this painting
by Piero della Francesca,

847
00:48:28,280 --> 00:48:30,740
because he is native of Tuscany,

848
00:48:30,824 --> 00:48:32,283
and because
that image of the Madonna

849
00:48:32,367 --> 00:48:35,912
protecting even the sinners I thought
would be important to Frances.

850
00:48:35,996 --> 00:48:38,039
FRANCES: Aunt Mary is
everywhere here,

851
00:48:38,123 --> 00:48:40,166
her calm presence assuring us

852
00:48:40,918 --> 00:48:43,586
that all things will go on
as they have before.

853
00:48:43,670 --> 00:48:47,423
WELLS: This Christmas scene
made me feel like a real movie director.

854
00:48:47,507 --> 00:48:51,260
We had snow. We had extras.
We had a manger.

855
00:48:51,345 --> 00:48:53,095
You know,
what more could you ask for?

856
00:48:53,180 --> 00:48:55,806
Just about everybody in this scene
is recognizable to me,

857
00:48:55,891 --> 00:48:58,142
because Cortona
was such a small town

858
00:48:58,226 --> 00:49:01,103
and everybody who lived there
wanted to be an extra in the movie,

859
00:49:01,188 --> 00:49:03,773
and so the people that you see
crossing back and forth here

860
00:49:03,857 --> 00:49:07,109
were also really the people
working in the cafes

861
00:49:07,194 --> 00:49:10,738
and at the hair salon
and in the grocery stores.

862
00:49:13,450 --> 00:49:15,117
Bellissima.

863
00:49:15,202 --> 00:49:17,995
What a beautiful family. Wow.

864
00:49:18,455 --> 00:49:19,538
WELLS: When l watch this scene

865
00:49:19,623 --> 00:49:22,667
I am reminded that we had
a lot of snow issues that night.

866
00:49:22,751 --> 00:49:26,462
We had a very noisy snow machine
for covering the entire piazza.

867
00:49:26,546 --> 00:49:30,716
And I had asked that we find a way
to have snow fall on actors quietly

868
00:49:30,801 --> 00:49:32,760
when we were in their close-ups,

869
00:49:33,220 --> 00:49:35,721
but this quiet way
never exactly materialized,

870
00:49:35,806 --> 00:49:38,975
and the machines that we did have
would've drowned out their dialogue,

871
00:49:39,059 --> 00:49:41,560
and I would've had to replace it all later.

872
00:49:41,645 --> 00:49:45,314
So, instead, l settled on having guys
off-camera throw snow into the air

873
00:49:45,399 --> 00:49:47,817
and fan it in the actors' direction.

874
00:49:47,901 --> 00:49:52,071
This was quieter, but as you can see,
it was also, shall we say, inconsistent.

875
00:49:52,614 --> 00:49:55,741
There are so many compromises
that you make along the way.

876
00:49:56,493 --> 00:50:00,329
-Merry Christmas, Signora Mayes.
-Buon Natale.

877
00:50:00,664 --> 00:50:04,250
WELLS: Frances Mayes, in her book,
talks a lot about food.

878
00:50:05,502 --> 00:50:09,213
It's a very important element
of Italian life.

879
00:50:09,297 --> 00:50:12,091
And Frances, as a poet,
writes about it in such a way

880
00:50:12,175 --> 00:50:13,926
that food takes on a lot

881
00:50:14,344 --> 00:50:16,887
of other kinds of significance.

882
00:50:16,972 --> 00:50:19,348
And I had decided early on

883
00:50:19,433 --> 00:50:24,186
that I wasn't going to try and make
a great movie about cooking.

884
00:50:24,271 --> 00:50:26,564
There are some fantastic movies
about cooking,

885
00:50:26,648 --> 00:50:29,358
like Eat Drink Man Woman
or Like Water for Chocolate.

886
00:50:29,443 --> 00:50:31,527
Those are movies
that made it very clear to me

887
00:50:31,611 --> 00:50:34,030
that I wasn't going to try and do that.

888
00:50:34,114 --> 00:50:38,159
I had too much story to tell
to center the movie around food.

889
00:50:38,243 --> 00:50:40,494
It wasn't the way I'd structured the film.

890
00:50:40,579 --> 00:50:43,748
And I thought that a little
would go a long way.

891
00:50:44,666 --> 00:50:46,959
So this is pretty much the only time

892
00:50:47,044 --> 00:50:49,962
you see a lot of cooking
going on in the movie.

893
00:50:50,047 --> 00:50:53,257
I like the fact that she feeds
her immediate family,

894
00:50:53,341 --> 00:50:55,509
the guys that she sees every day.

895
00:50:55,594 --> 00:50:57,261
And the food that you see here

896
00:50:57,345 --> 00:51:00,598
was prepared by Antonella
from Tonino's Restaurant,

897
00:51:00,682 --> 00:51:02,266
it's a place that we loved to eat

898
00:51:02,350 --> 00:51:05,227
and where they were very,
very nice to us during the shoot.

899
00:51:05,604 --> 00:51:07,146
We would always go there
on Friday nights.

900
00:51:07,230 --> 00:51:10,232
And they would bring out dish
after dish after dish,

901
00:51:10,317 --> 00:51:12,068
each one more delicious than the last,

902
00:51:12,152 --> 00:51:14,820
and for me,
I took a lot of pleasure out of it,

903
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:16,906
because I was really working
such long hours

904
00:51:16,990 --> 00:51:20,618
going to the dailies after shooting,
and we were shooting six-day weeks,

905
00:51:20,702 --> 00:51:23,621
and when we went to Tonino's
every now and then and had a meal,

906
00:51:23,705 --> 00:51:26,248
that was a real moment of relaxation
for us all.

907
00:51:30,837 --> 00:51:32,338
Bravo!

908
00:51:34,966 --> 00:51:37,218
Bravo! Bravo!

909
00:51:39,846 --> 00:51:45,810
Riusciro, riuscirai, riuscira, riusciremo,
riuscirete, riusciranno.

910
00:51:45,894 --> 00:51:48,854
-Good.
-See, Frances? Italian is easy.

911
00:51:50,482 --> 00:51:53,109
WELLS: It's true that I co-authored
the screenplay

912
00:51:53,193 --> 00:51:56,946
for George of the Jungle,
but this is not an homage to moi.

913
00:51:57,364 --> 00:52:00,491
I knew that I wanted to stick
an American movie out there,

914
00:52:00,575 --> 00:52:03,536
and since my film was
for the Walt Disney Company,

915
00:52:03,620 --> 00:52:06,288
I chose a film from their library
to make life simple.

916
00:52:06,373 --> 00:52:09,458
And itjust seemed funny to me
to have Pawel say outside,

917
00:52:09,543 --> 00:52:11,418
"See, Frances, ltalian is easy."

918
00:52:11,503 --> 00:52:14,004
And then to see that even George
of the Jungle could speak Italian.

919
00:52:15,715 --> 00:52:18,175
Have you talked to her yet?

920
00:52:20,428 --> 00:52:23,389
Si. I have talked to her.

921
00:52:24,349 --> 00:52:27,017
Why don't you go sit next to her? Go on.

922
00:52:27,102 --> 00:52:28,561
Okay.

923
00:52:29,938 --> 00:52:33,983
WELLS: This scene is shot inside
the Teatro Signorelli in Cortona.

924
00:52:34,067 --> 00:52:35,484
A beautiful movie theater

925
00:52:35,569 --> 00:52:38,821
where this movie
will probably play someday soon.

926
00:52:52,794 --> 00:52:54,753
Katherine?

927
00:52:57,591 --> 00:52:59,341
WELLS: l love the exterior
of this building.

928
00:52:59,426 --> 00:53:01,343
These are the rewards
of shooting on location.

929
00:53:01,428 --> 00:53:03,179
If you tried to recreate that somewhere,

930
00:53:03,263 --> 00:53:06,891
you would never come up with
something as fantastic as that facade.

931
00:53:08,935 --> 00:53:10,978
This set we dressed with furniture,

932
00:53:11,062 --> 00:53:13,772
but the walls are original
from Napoleon's era.

933
00:53:13,857 --> 00:53:18,319
As a matter of fact, Napoleon
actually slept in this room, so they said.

934
00:53:21,948 --> 00:53:25,951
-I think I'll come back another time.
-Why? You don't bother me.

935
00:53:26,036 --> 00:53:29,121
Frances, this is Zeus.

936
00:53:29,247 --> 00:53:31,957
WELLS: Ah, Zeus.
Zeus in the digital underwear.

937
00:53:32,417 --> 00:53:34,001
Stare closely at the buttocks

938
00:53:34,085 --> 00:53:35,502
and you will see
that they move separately

939
00:53:35,587 --> 00:53:37,129
from the fabric that is covering them.

940
00:53:37,756 --> 00:53:40,174
Although the CGl guys
did a very good job.

941
00:53:41,301 --> 00:53:42,259
You see, what happened here

942
00:53:42,344 --> 00:53:45,763
is that I was contractually obligated
to deliver a PG-13 movie.

943
00:53:46,556 --> 00:53:51,143
And originally that actor
came out with a nude butt.

944
00:53:52,020 --> 00:53:53,646
And I received an R rating for the film,

945
00:53:53,813 --> 00:53:56,190
even though
actually the scene is very innocent.

946
00:53:56,775 --> 00:54:00,236
So in order to roII that back to PG-13,

947
00:54:00,320 --> 00:54:02,821
we decided to put some underwear
on Zeus' bum.

948
00:54:03,907 --> 00:54:07,201
And to that end, there are gentlemen

949
00:54:07,285 --> 00:54:10,162
at a certain visual effects house
in Los Angeles

950
00:54:10,247 --> 00:54:12,623
who worked many, many long hours

951
00:54:12,707 --> 00:54:17,002
staring at the musculature
of his behind trying to figure out

952
00:54:17,087 --> 00:54:19,755
how to make those digital underpants
move accordingly.

953
00:54:19,839 --> 00:54:21,715
I just got here. I just walked in the door.

954
00:54:21,800 --> 00:54:24,635
How are you ever going to be happy
if you keep wallowing?

955
00:54:24,719 --> 00:54:28,681
WELLS: ln this scene, Lindsay talks
about her ladybug philosophy.

956
00:54:30,475 --> 00:54:32,851
This was actually something
that came to me

957
00:54:32,936 --> 00:54:35,062
through being the mother
of a two-and-a-half-year-old

958
00:54:35,146 --> 00:54:37,356
who is always on the lookout
for ladybugs.

959
00:54:41,236 --> 00:54:42,236
So?

960
00:54:42,362 --> 00:54:46,365
So, go work on your house
and forget about it.

961
00:54:47,909 --> 00:54:49,660
I said go!

962
00:54:49,744 --> 00:54:51,453
I'm going!

963
00:54:55,333 --> 00:54:56,750
WELLS: At this point in the film,
I felt like

964
00:54:56,835 --> 00:54:58,377
we all wanted to get going somewhere

965
00:54:58,461 --> 00:54:59,920
other than Cortona.

966
00:55:00,005 --> 00:55:01,297
I figured that the character

967
00:55:01,381 --> 00:55:04,800
was probably starting to feel
claustrophobic in that environment,

968
00:55:04,884 --> 00:55:08,387
and stuck with the Polish guys
that were driving her a little bit crazy

969
00:55:08,471 --> 00:55:10,097
since she was seeing them all the time.

970
00:55:10,432 --> 00:55:12,516
FRANCES: There comes a time
when you no longer want

971
00:55:12,600 --> 00:55:14,143
shaky guys staring at you,

972
00:55:14,227 --> 00:55:15,728
thinking God knows what,

973
00:55:15,812 --> 00:55:16,979
whispering things in Polish

974
00:55:17,063 --> 00:55:19,773
you're really, really glad
you don't understand.

975
00:55:19,899 --> 00:55:23,152
"Kocham ciebie," "Nie rozumiem..."

976
00:55:23,236 --> 00:55:24,987
I mean, there's only so much of that
you can take

977
00:55:25,071 --> 00:55:28,240
before there comes a time
when you reallyjust have to get out.

978
00:55:31,494 --> 00:55:35,247
WELLS: We moved to Rome
and shot there for about seven days.

979
00:55:35,623 --> 00:55:37,166
This is the Vittoriano.

980
00:55:37,250 --> 00:55:40,002
And I actually saw it
out the window of my apartment

981
00:55:40,086 --> 00:55:41,503
that we rented in Rome.

982
00:55:45,842 --> 00:55:47,301
It was exciting to be shooting

983
00:55:47,385 --> 00:55:50,095
in the center
of this fantastically beautiful city.

984
00:55:51,056 --> 00:55:54,433
We chose a street for this scene
that's known for its antique shops.

985
00:55:54,809 --> 00:55:56,685
Traditionally, people work
outside their shops

986
00:55:56,770 --> 00:55:59,688
refurbishing furniture,
which is what we depicted here.

987
00:56:04,110 --> 00:56:05,986
-Mamma mia!
-Signorina.

988
00:56:08,323 --> 00:56:09,448
Great.

989
00:56:12,118 --> 00:56:13,285
Hilarious.

990
00:56:14,704 --> 00:56:15,913
Bye.

991
00:56:18,166 --> 00:56:20,334
WELLS: Any woman
who's ever been alone in Italy

992
00:56:20,418 --> 00:56:22,127
understands what this scene is about.

993
00:56:28,510 --> 00:56:31,136
You are American, eh?

994
00:56:31,596 --> 00:56:33,347
-English?
-Irish?

995
00:56:35,767 --> 00:56:38,060
There you are.
I've been looking for you everywhere.

996
00:56:39,145 --> 00:56:41,647
WELLS: When l wanted
to cast Marcello,

997
00:56:41,731 --> 00:56:45,234
it wasn't important to me
that I cast a great-looking actor.

998
00:56:45,318 --> 00:56:49,238
I did not set out to find somebody
as handsome as Raoul obviously is.

999
00:56:49,989 --> 00:56:53,158
But I was very concerned
about finding somebody

1000
00:56:53,243 --> 00:56:55,244
who could hold his own
opposite Diane Lane,

1001
00:56:55,328 --> 00:56:56,787
and who was really Italian

1002
00:56:56,871 --> 00:57:01,583
and who could really speak English
well enough to play the scenes.

1003
00:57:01,668 --> 00:57:04,336
Raoul is a superstar in Italy.

1004
00:57:04,963 --> 00:57:07,381
There were times when we would
walk down the street together

1005
00:57:07,465 --> 00:57:08,674
and we hadn't gone five blocks

1006
00:57:08,758 --> 00:57:11,051
before we had attracted a crowd
of 200 people.

1007
00:57:12,679 --> 00:57:15,722
But you would never know that
by working with him,

1008
00:57:15,807 --> 00:57:19,685
because he is a tremendously modest,
gentlemanly person.

1009
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:23,105
-You are too late.
-I'm sorry?

1010
00:57:23,189 --> 00:57:24,857
I have already found somebody else.

1011
00:57:28,194 --> 00:57:29,403
My loss.

1012
00:57:29,487 --> 00:57:31,071
WELLS: Raoul and Diane
liked each other a lot.

1013
00:57:31,156 --> 00:57:34,074
And it was always fun
having the two of them together.

1014
00:57:34,534 --> 00:57:35,909
They had a good rapport.

1015
00:57:36,077 --> 00:57:37,953
And I especially liked the way

1016
00:57:38,037 --> 00:57:41,665
Raoul had a charming
and kind of trustworthy presence.

1017
00:57:41,749 --> 00:57:47,045
He didn't seem like the typical
Latin lover, wolf-whistling,

1018
00:57:47,130 --> 00:57:48,797
sleaze ball kind of guy.

1019
00:57:49,632 --> 00:57:51,884
I felt that I understood
why Diane's character

1020
00:57:51,968 --> 00:57:53,343
would be attracted to him

1021
00:57:53,428 --> 00:57:56,180
and willing to jump in his car
afterjust having met him.

1022
00:57:59,225 --> 00:58:01,101
-Is it far?
-About three hours.

1023
00:58:01,853 --> 00:58:05,189
-Two, if I drive fast.
-Two hours?

1024
00:58:08,151 --> 00:58:09,818
WELLS: When Frances meets MarceIIo,

1025
00:58:09,903 --> 00:58:12,279
it's clearly something
the audience has been waiting for.

1026
00:58:12,530 --> 00:58:14,281
Ever since Patti said,
"Have you met him yet,

1027
00:58:14,365 --> 00:58:16,617
"the man you're going to meet,"
we've been on the lookout

1028
00:58:16,701 --> 00:58:19,620
for this romantic interlude in her life.

1029
00:58:19,746 --> 00:58:24,333
And I felt like it's also part and parcel
with stories about people on the road.

1030
00:58:24,417 --> 00:58:26,919
It's the kind of time
when you are open to things,

1031
00:58:27,003 --> 00:58:30,589
and you have adventures
and you let yourself talk to strangers.

1032
00:58:30,673 --> 00:58:33,383
And I like the adventurous aspect of it.

1033
00:58:34,594 --> 00:58:37,596
But more than that,
this was an opportunity for me

1034
00:58:37,680 --> 00:58:41,517
to show her coming back to life
and taking chances.

1035
00:58:43,311 --> 00:58:44,686
You're willing.

1036
00:58:45,730 --> 00:58:48,524
WELLS: There are expectations built up
between the two of them

1037
00:58:48,608 --> 00:58:50,275
in these scenes that are paid off

1038
00:58:50,360 --> 00:58:54,863
in an unconventional manner
later on in the movie.

1039
00:58:55,156 --> 00:58:57,866
It was a chance to sort of
play with some stereotypes

1040
00:58:57,951 --> 00:58:59,451
and make fun of them at the same time.

1041
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:03,121
The comedy was very important
in order to accomplish that.

1042
00:59:05,124 --> 00:59:06,708
Yellow light, decoration.

1043
00:59:06,960 --> 00:59:09,461
-And what about red lights?
-Just a suggestion.

1044
00:59:09,546 --> 00:59:10,546
(LAUGHS)

1045
00:59:14,259 --> 00:59:15,801
WELLS: And now we are in
southern Italy

1046
00:59:15,885 --> 00:59:18,220
on the Amalfi Coast and that's Positano.

1047
00:59:18,680 --> 00:59:22,224
And this is one of the most famous
stretches of road in the world.

1048
00:59:23,893 --> 00:59:25,811
This piece of music
is one of the first things

1049
00:59:25,895 --> 00:59:27,396
that Chris wrote for the movie.

1050
00:59:27,480 --> 00:59:30,065
And he didn't write it
for any scene in particular.

1051
00:59:30,149 --> 00:59:32,651
And it was so romantic,
I wanted to find a place for it,

1052
00:59:32,735 --> 00:59:34,319
but wasn't sure that I would.

1053
00:59:34,654 --> 00:59:37,531
Then we realized
that it suited this drive very nicely.

1054
00:59:39,409 --> 00:59:43,328
Once again, we hadn't made the
proper sacrifices to the weather gods,

1055
00:59:43,413 --> 00:59:47,040
because we were absolutely dogged
by rain when we were in Positano.

1056
00:59:47,500 --> 00:59:50,002
You are barely seeing
any complete takes here,

1057
00:59:50,086 --> 00:59:52,087
because we always had to stop

1058
00:59:52,171 --> 00:59:54,840
when it would suddenly begin raining
and we'd start over again.

1059
00:59:55,508 --> 00:59:59,219
It's miraculous that this sequence
comes off as looking somewhat sunny

1060
00:59:59,304 --> 01:00:02,014
when, in fact, we were getting
rained out every 10 minutes.

1061
01:00:07,937 --> 01:00:08,979
This is your bar.

1062
01:00:09,689 --> 01:00:12,733
We are a family. I work here.

1063
01:00:12,817 --> 01:00:14,735
And I sleep there...

1064
01:00:16,779 --> 01:00:18,155
WELLS: During rehearsal week,
there was a day

1065
01:00:18,239 --> 01:00:19,823
that Raoul and I spent together.

1066
01:00:19,907 --> 01:00:22,034
And we had some lunch
and then, afterwards,

1067
01:00:22,118 --> 01:00:25,871
he poured me a glass of limoncello,
the liqueur made from lemons

1068
01:00:25,955 --> 01:00:27,497
that come from the south of Italy.

1069
01:00:27,999 --> 01:00:29,750
And he told me
that he knew how to make it.

1070
01:00:29,834 --> 01:00:32,252
And I asked him
to explain that process to me.

1071
01:00:32,545 --> 01:00:35,088
And as he did, l realized that

1072
01:00:35,173 --> 01:00:38,258
I was looking
at a rather intoxicating person

1073
01:00:38,343 --> 01:00:40,969
who was in the middle
of a pretty sensuous description

1074
01:00:41,054 --> 01:00:42,304
of how these things are made.

1075
01:00:42,722 --> 01:00:45,140
And I thought it was funny, actually,

1076
01:00:45,224 --> 01:00:46,725
and that it really
needed to go in the movie.

1077
01:00:46,809 --> 01:00:49,436
That it could be something
that he could do with Frances

1078
01:00:49,520 --> 01:00:52,022
that could unsettle her
and make her smile.

1079
01:00:53,232 --> 01:00:55,859
So I told Raoul
that when we got to Positano,

1080
01:00:55,943 --> 01:00:59,196
I would ask him to tell Frances
how limoncello was made,

1081
01:00:59,280 --> 01:01:00,781
but that I would never write the scene

1082
01:01:00,865 --> 01:01:02,991
and he should
never rehearse the scene,

1083
01:01:03,076 --> 01:01:07,245
that he should just let it go
from his mind and do it on the day.

1084
01:01:08,748 --> 01:01:11,166
I love the way it turned out.
I think Diane helped a little bit

1085
01:01:11,250 --> 01:01:13,919
with nudging him with her foot
under the table.

1086
01:01:14,754 --> 01:01:17,756
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

1087
01:01:19,217 --> 01:01:21,134
My nephew.

1088
01:01:21,219 --> 01:01:22,302
Yes.

1089
01:01:30,228 --> 01:01:33,647
WELLS: The Amalfi Coast is usually
absolutely packed with tourists,

1090
01:01:33,731 --> 01:01:35,524
but it becomes deserted
in late November,

1091
01:01:35,608 --> 01:01:37,192
which is when we were there.

1092
01:01:39,779 --> 01:01:41,988
But I love the way
the umbrellas looked on the beach,

1093
01:01:42,073 --> 01:01:43,824
and I put them back out there
for the scene.

1094
01:01:50,623 --> 01:01:55,585
This scene is very playful
and it's also quite absurd,

1095
01:01:55,670 --> 01:01:58,672
but it's an absurdity
that I recognize from life.

1096
01:02:00,800 --> 01:02:03,552
There's a certain giddiness
that exists between people

1097
01:02:03,636 --> 01:02:05,512
who know something's
about to happen.

1098
01:02:05,596 --> 01:02:08,473
And the anticipation is killing them
in this scene.

1099
01:02:08,933 --> 01:02:10,809
I like their awkward goofiness.

1100
01:02:10,893 --> 01:02:14,146
And I am also guilty of liking a man
who is nice to kittens.

1101
01:02:14,772 --> 01:02:16,273
I had the love interest
do the same thing

1102
01:02:16,357 --> 01:02:18,900
in a movie I wrote called
The Truth About Cats & Dogs.

1103
01:02:19,110 --> 01:02:22,279
Ben Chaplin pets a cat
and Janeane Garofalo falls in love.

1104
01:02:22,739 --> 01:02:25,073
l, of course, have never
personally experienced

1105
01:02:25,158 --> 01:02:26,324
anything remotely like that.

1106
01:02:38,087 --> 01:02:42,966
I run into you in the street in Rome
and... And now we're here and...

1107
01:02:43,176 --> 01:02:44,760
Didn't you have some plans today?

1108
01:02:44,844 --> 01:02:47,554
Didn't you have something
you had to do?

1109
01:02:49,640 --> 01:02:51,016
So what?

1110
01:02:52,393 --> 01:02:56,646
If you smash into something good,

1111
01:02:56,731 --> 01:03:00,192
you should hold on
until it's time to let go.

1112
01:03:01,694 --> 01:03:03,111
WELLS: Raoul spoke English
pretty well,

1113
01:03:03,196 --> 01:03:05,322
but he did make
the kind of idiomatic mistakes

1114
01:03:05,406 --> 01:03:07,532
that I put into the script.

1115
01:03:07,617 --> 01:03:10,535
But he frequently furnished his own,
which I loved.

1116
01:03:13,289 --> 01:03:15,457
I like Diane's nervousness
in this scene.

1117
01:03:15,541 --> 01:03:18,043
She clearly is on edge.

1118
01:03:18,461 --> 01:03:22,047
Her character feeling that
this is reallyjust too much to take.

1119
01:03:22,632 --> 01:03:26,384
And I like the way that she laughs
at his ridiculous line.

1120
01:03:27,595 --> 01:03:28,637
What?

1121
01:03:30,932 --> 01:03:32,933
WELLS: To me,
this kind of back and forth

1122
01:03:33,017 --> 01:03:36,311
is part and parcel
with international relationships

1123
01:03:36,395 --> 01:03:38,688
and the kinds of misunderstandings
and preconceptions

1124
01:03:38,773 --> 01:03:40,148
that we have about each other.

1125
01:03:40,233 --> 01:03:41,441
Thank you.

1126
01:03:47,740 --> 01:03:49,783
Marcello, I'm sorry.

1127
01:03:49,867 --> 01:03:51,368
I'm so sorry.

1128
01:03:52,787 --> 01:03:56,414
I'm sorry. I...
I'm really nervous, you know?

1129
01:03:57,416 --> 01:03:59,543
I was married for a long time,

1130
01:03:59,627 --> 01:04:03,380
and since then
there hasn't been anybody.

1131
01:04:03,923 --> 01:04:06,758
WELLS: All this hyper-romantic stuff
that's going on here,

1132
01:04:07,552 --> 01:04:09,928
it's something I thought
was important to do,

1133
01:04:10,012 --> 01:04:14,516
so that Frances could be
mistaken in believing for a while

1134
01:04:14,600 --> 01:04:17,894
that some kind of fairy-tale ending
could happen to her.

1135
01:04:19,772 --> 01:04:23,733
It's all part of this
kind of extended cruelty

1136
01:04:23,818 --> 01:04:27,654
that I'm inflicting on her
as part of the journey that she's on.

1137
01:04:29,282 --> 01:04:30,907
Yeah.

1138
01:04:34,871 --> 01:04:38,164
WELLS: lt's kind of like Lucy holding
the football for Charlie Brown to kick.

1139
01:04:38,291 --> 01:04:42,335
It always gets pulled away.
But right now she is in the thrall of it.

1140
01:04:53,639 --> 01:04:56,433
I didn't use a lot of magic realism
in the film,

1141
01:04:56,517 --> 01:04:59,686
but so many of the naturally available
shots in Italy,

1142
01:04:59,770 --> 01:05:01,563
like the fields of sunflowers,
for example,

1143
01:05:01,647 --> 01:05:03,064
were so extreme

1144
01:05:03,149 --> 01:05:04,983
that they allowed me
to dabble in effects shots

1145
01:05:05,067 --> 01:05:06,484
without sacrificing tone.

1146
01:05:07,236 --> 01:05:09,571
I really only used them
when they had storytelling value.

1147
01:05:10,072 --> 01:05:12,616
Like here, where l used it
to show passage of time.

1148
01:05:12,909 --> 01:05:16,161
It made the transition from the beach
to the tabletop feel less abrupt.

1149
01:05:22,376 --> 01:05:24,920
-Francesca.
-Yes?

1150
01:05:28,341 --> 01:05:31,259
I'm going to make love all over you.

1151
01:05:31,344 --> 01:05:43,980
Okay.

1152
01:06:09,256 --> 01:06:12,258
WELLS: This love scene
between Diane and Raoul

1153
01:06:12,343 --> 01:06:16,054
was shot on the first day
that they worked together.

1154
01:06:16,138 --> 01:06:17,806
And, of course,
it wasn't planned that way,

1155
01:06:17,890 --> 01:06:18,890
but this was the only scene

1156
01:06:18,975 --> 01:06:22,018
that we had to shoot inside
when we were in Positano.

1157
01:06:22,520 --> 01:06:25,480
And it was scheduled to be
at the end of the five days

1158
01:06:25,564 --> 01:06:28,650
that we spent in that town.
But, of course, it rained on day one,

1159
01:06:28,734 --> 01:06:31,569
and this interior was our cover set,

1160
01:06:31,737 --> 01:06:34,948
the place that we could film that day
since it was pouring rain outside.

1161
01:06:35,366 --> 01:06:37,575
So they ended up
having to do this scene first.

1162
01:06:39,954 --> 01:06:45,208
This is when I really admire actors.
(LAUGHING) lt must be so hard.

1163
01:06:45,626 --> 01:06:50,463
Imagine eight of us just a few inches
away from them, staring intently.

1164
01:06:51,257 --> 01:06:55,051
And they don't even know each other,
and Raoul is married and has two kids,

1165
01:06:55,136 --> 01:06:57,262
and Diane is in love
with somebody else,

1166
01:06:57,388 --> 01:06:59,180
and here they are, acting.

1167
01:06:59,890 --> 01:07:03,101
At least, for the next five minutes.

1168
01:07:04,395 --> 01:07:07,772
Okay. Okay.

1169
01:07:11,861 --> 01:07:14,654
WELLS: I admire them, because I think
it takes a lot of concentration

1170
01:07:14,739 --> 01:07:18,116
to get through a scene like this
naturally and with focus,

1171
01:07:18,200 --> 01:07:21,411
when just a few feet away,
there are a bunch of crew members

1172
01:07:21,495 --> 01:07:25,874
who are searching their pockets
for a mint or trying not to sneeze.

1173
01:07:28,961 --> 01:07:32,047
You have to promise to come back here.

1174
01:07:33,132 --> 01:07:35,216
Promise me.

1175
01:07:35,301 --> 01:07:36,968
When?

1176
01:07:37,720 --> 01:07:40,180
Can you come this weekend?

1177
01:07:41,599 --> 01:07:43,808
Well, I think so.

1178
01:07:45,561 --> 01:07:47,520
-You think so?
-Mm.

1179
01:07:49,190 --> 01:07:51,316
You think so?

1180
01:07:57,740 --> 01:08:01,326
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes!

1181
01:08:01,410 --> 01:08:03,995
Yes! Yes! Yes!

1182
01:08:05,039 --> 01:08:06,664
WELLS: This was a fun scene to shoot.

1183
01:08:07,208 --> 01:08:09,167
We didn't rehearse it.
We just blocked it.

1184
01:08:09,251 --> 01:08:11,086
Diane clearly knew
what the scene was about.

1185
01:08:11,295 --> 01:08:14,839
I've still got it. I've still got it.
I've still got it!

1186
01:08:15,007 --> 01:08:17,008
Thank God!

1187
01:08:18,260 --> 01:08:19,594
Oh, yeah.

1188
01:08:28,938 --> 01:08:31,731
WELLS: Nicoletta and I
decided that Katherine

1189
01:08:31,816 --> 01:08:34,317
should be having lunch with nuns.

1190
01:08:34,401 --> 01:08:35,944
And since she is concerned

1191
01:08:36,028 --> 01:08:38,446
about always dressing appropriately
for the occasion,

1192
01:08:38,531 --> 01:08:41,282
she would be
in her quasi nun outfit herself.

1193
01:08:42,201 --> 01:08:43,952
I love the whipped cream
on that one nun's lip.

1194
01:08:45,538 --> 01:08:46,871
Tomorrow.

1195
01:08:57,716 --> 01:09:00,385
WELLS: This is a moment that I like
very much in the movie

1196
01:09:01,428 --> 01:09:04,639
when Diane is walking
out of the house happy,

1197
01:09:04,723 --> 01:09:07,684
her thoughts about Marcello.
She is on her way to Positano.

1198
01:09:07,768 --> 01:09:10,478
And then, we see her stop
and a look comes over her.

1199
01:09:11,647 --> 01:09:14,649
And we are not at all clear
on who she sees.

1200
01:09:20,531 --> 01:09:23,741
And it's a wonderful surprise
that it's Patti.

1201
01:09:30,457 --> 01:09:33,751
-Look at you!
-God damn it, Frances.

1202
01:09:36,881 --> 01:09:38,006
Hi.

1203
01:09:38,090 --> 01:09:40,884
-What?
-I gotta go pee!

1204
01:09:42,178 --> 01:09:45,930
WELLS: Sandra works hard on her
characters. She really likes to prepare.

1205
01:09:46,223 --> 01:09:47,682
And I remember she told me

1206
01:09:47,766 --> 01:09:50,935
that once Nicoletta had given her
this pregnancy pillow,

1207
01:09:51,020 --> 01:09:53,104
she wore it around for weeks
in Los Angeles

1208
01:09:53,189 --> 01:09:55,565
before she flew out to Italy.

1209
01:09:56,233 --> 01:09:58,234
And wore the belly on the airplane

1210
01:09:58,319 --> 01:10:01,905
where she was treated with deference
and respect by all.

1211
01:10:02,740 --> 01:10:04,532
I think she exploited it a little bit.

1212
01:10:07,203 --> 01:10:09,078
Oh, jeez...

1213
01:10:14,543 --> 01:10:16,961
So, what's it like
having one of these in Cortona?

1214
01:10:18,881 --> 01:10:22,759
I hear the town midwife's pretty good.
She puts a knife under the bed.

1215
01:10:22,968 --> 01:10:25,303
To cut the pain.

1216
01:10:25,971 --> 01:10:28,223
Florence is an hour away.

1217
01:10:28,307 --> 01:10:31,476
You're gonna be delivering this baby
in a hospital gown designed by Armani.

1218
01:10:32,394 --> 01:10:33,519
(PATTI CHUCKLES)

1219
01:10:49,328 --> 01:10:53,206
WELLS: Sandra did about three
takes of this. This is the second one.

1220
01:10:54,333 --> 01:10:57,669
I never found it necessary
with any actor on this movie

1221
01:10:57,753 --> 01:10:59,337
to do a lot of takes.

1222
01:11:00,506 --> 01:11:05,009
Every one of them was the kind of actor
that is ready to go on take one

1223
01:11:05,094 --> 01:11:07,679
and gives you something
that you can use.

1224
01:11:08,514 --> 01:11:11,724
I could've cut this entire movie
with the first take of every scene.

1225
01:11:13,185 --> 01:11:15,853
Oh, Jesus, Frances!

1226
01:11:20,567 --> 01:11:22,694
How do you do it?

1227
01:11:26,031 --> 01:11:29,033
How do you ever breathe again?

1228
01:11:37,251 --> 01:11:38,793
Pretty soon.

1229
01:11:43,716 --> 01:11:45,717
God, I missed you.

1230
01:11:49,847 --> 01:11:52,974
WELLS: l shot this phallic tree,
because I thought it represented

1231
01:11:53,058 --> 01:11:55,059
what was missing
in the lives of these women.

1232
01:11:55,728 --> 01:11:57,228
Don't worry, I'm just kidding.

1233
01:11:58,063 --> 01:12:00,732
(CHUCKLING) The importance
and depth of female friendship

1234
01:12:00,816 --> 01:12:03,401
is obviously a great big part
of this movie.

1235
01:12:03,485 --> 01:12:05,903
And Diane and Sandra
captured it beautifully.

1236
01:12:06,238 --> 01:12:08,740
I especially like their performance
in this scene.

1237
01:12:08,824 --> 01:12:10,116
I think it's very tender.

1238
01:12:14,621 --> 01:12:19,083
There's something strange
about these trees. It's like they know.

1239
01:12:19,168 --> 01:12:22,003
And they know
that we know that they know.

1240
01:12:22,087 --> 01:12:25,381
They're creepy. Creepy Italian trees.

1241
01:12:25,591 --> 01:12:28,343
The baby's gonna like them 'cause
he's gonna be a creepy Italian baby

1242
01:12:28,427 --> 01:12:30,970
who goes around saying,
"Ciao, Mamma, "

1243
01:12:31,096 --> 01:12:33,639
and doing that backward
hand-wave thing.

1244
01:12:36,643 --> 01:12:37,935
Life is strange.

1245
01:12:44,360 --> 01:12:48,279
-Where were you going when I arrived?
-Nowhere important.

1246
01:12:48,364 --> 01:12:50,281
What's he like?

1247
01:12:50,366 --> 01:12:52,075
He's a creepy Italian.

1248
01:12:52,159 --> 01:12:54,494
-So go see him.
-I will.

1249
01:12:54,578 --> 01:12:57,955
I wanna spend time
with my creepy American friend.

1250
01:12:58,040 --> 01:13:00,166
I refuse to screw up your love life.

1251
01:13:00,250 --> 01:13:03,753
Don't be ridiculous, Patti.
You are my love life.

1252
01:13:05,798 --> 01:13:09,300
WELLS: Ah! The goat.
We shot him in pre-production.

1253
01:13:09,676 --> 01:13:11,719
It's a very nice-looking goat.
It was very clean.

1254
01:13:11,804 --> 01:13:14,389
We had to dirty it up a little bit,
because the goat owner

1255
01:13:14,473 --> 01:13:16,474
had given her a shampoo
before she arrived.

1256
01:13:50,217 --> 01:13:53,511
This is the third time in the movie
that Frances notices the spigot.

1257
01:13:53,929 --> 01:13:56,264
The first time was on the first day
that she entered the house

1258
01:13:56,348 --> 01:13:58,349
and she walked into it
and gave herself a bruise.

1259
01:13:59,309 --> 01:14:01,352
And the second time was
after she purchased the house

1260
01:14:01,437 --> 01:14:04,105
and she realized
that even if she turns the knob,

1261
01:14:04,189 --> 01:14:05,731
she couldn't get any water out of it.

1262
01:14:06,608 --> 01:14:09,694
And here in this scene, it's the first time
that she notices that it's dripping.

1263
01:14:09,945 --> 01:14:13,030
There's hot water in the toilet bowl.

1264
01:14:15,200 --> 01:14:18,327
Oh, my God. That's close to boiling.

1265
01:14:19,371 --> 01:14:21,372
They must've
crossed a pipe somewhere.

1266
01:14:21,457 --> 01:14:24,625
WELLS: Certain jokes keep me
laughing an abnormally long time.

1267
01:14:24,710 --> 01:14:25,918
And this is one of them.

1268
01:14:26,044 --> 01:14:28,379
Unless you wanna
give your ass a facial.

1269
01:14:28,464 --> 01:14:31,132
That's a contradiction in terms.

1270
01:14:31,216 --> 01:14:34,385
I guess it'd be more of an ass-cial.

1271
01:14:35,095 --> 01:14:37,096
(SUPPRESSED GIGGLING
NEXT DOOR)

1272
01:14:45,814 --> 01:14:48,483
WELLS: So Frances finds
the young lovers in her bed.

1273
01:14:48,567 --> 01:14:51,319
And this begins a section of the film

1274
01:14:51,403 --> 01:14:54,530
that I always thought of
as a kind of farce.

1275
01:14:55,032 --> 01:14:58,451
The same kind of farce that I studied
when I was in high school,

1276
01:14:58,535 --> 01:15:00,411
like Beaumarchais' plays.

1277
01:15:00,913 --> 01:15:04,081
St. Francesca,
patron saint of horny teenagers?

1278
01:15:04,791 --> 01:15:07,502
WELLS: There is class conflict.

1279
01:15:07,586 --> 01:15:10,338
There is people sneaking around
behind each other's backs.

1280
01:15:10,422 --> 01:15:11,714
There is plots going on.

1281
01:15:11,798 --> 01:15:16,427
There is the convenient appearance
of the nemesis atjust the right moment.

1282
01:15:16,762 --> 01:15:19,347
It's all in the style
of classic French farce.

1283
01:15:20,849 --> 01:15:22,475
Diventeremo pazzi l'uno senza l'altro.

1284
01:15:22,726 --> 01:15:25,561
Pawel ha detto che
lui commettera qualcosa di terribile!

1285
01:15:25,646 --> 01:15:28,356
Ha detto che diventera un assassino!

1286
01:15:28,440 --> 01:15:31,025
Ho provato a parlagli ma non vuole
ascoltarmi e non vuole capire...

1287
01:15:31,109 --> 01:15:33,611
Assassinate... Did you say assassinate?

1288
01:15:33,695 --> 01:15:36,030
Did she say that you were going
to assassinate somebody?

1289
01:15:36,114 --> 01:15:38,824
No. She misunderstand.

1290
01:15:38,909 --> 01:15:43,454
I didn't say... Amore,
I didn't say assassino.

1291
01:15:43,539 --> 01:15:45,373
WELLS: This is one of the many scenes
in the movie

1292
01:15:45,457 --> 01:15:48,042
that was kind of unwieldy
on the first cut.

1293
01:15:48,126 --> 01:15:51,879
And one of the many scenes
that Andy Marcus, my editor,

1294
01:15:51,964 --> 01:15:52,964
whipped into shape.

1295
01:15:54,132 --> 01:15:58,886
He and I had a great time together,
because we shared a sense of humor

1296
01:15:59,263 --> 01:16:00,930
and we were always
making each other laugh.

1297
01:16:01,557 --> 01:16:06,394
And I was always in favor of economy,
and that was a good thing,

1298
01:16:06,478 --> 01:16:09,313
because he was always
shoving economy down my throat

1299
01:16:10,440 --> 01:16:11,566
in a really nice way.

1300
01:16:11,733 --> 01:16:16,320
Because I can do it as good
as any Italian man, that's why.

1301
01:16:16,405 --> 01:16:18,239
And her father will see.

1302
01:16:18,323 --> 01:16:20,575
PLACIDO: (OUTSIDE)
Francesca? Francesca?

1303
01:16:20,659 --> 01:16:22,118
My father!

1304
01:16:23,078 --> 01:16:25,746
-Francesca.
-Placido, hi.

1305
01:16:25,831 --> 01:16:30,501
My daughter says you are taking her
to the festa in Montepulciano.

1306
01:16:30,586 --> 01:16:31,586
This is true?

1307
01:16:31,795 --> 01:16:33,504
Just a moment, please.

1308
01:16:37,384 --> 01:16:40,177
I told him you are taking me there
so he will stay home.

1309
01:16:40,262 --> 01:16:44,181
-I don't want to lie to your father.
-Oh, come on, Frances. Who cares?

1310
01:16:45,434 --> 01:16:46,726
PAWEL: Frances...

1311
01:16:47,936 --> 01:16:51,814
If I am not with her,
I will die of a broken heart.

1312
01:16:55,694 --> 01:16:57,820
You won't die.

1313
01:17:09,124 --> 01:17:11,334
WELLS: So here we are
in Montepulciano,

1314
01:17:11,418 --> 01:17:13,377
a neighboring town to Cortona.

1315
01:17:13,795 --> 01:17:16,672
And here is a depiction
of a flag throwing festival.

1316
01:17:17,007 --> 01:17:18,299
These take place all over Tuscany.

1317
01:17:18,383 --> 01:17:20,384
This was something
I was completely unaware of

1318
01:17:20,469 --> 01:17:22,428
when I was still in the States.

1319
01:17:24,181 --> 01:17:27,308
When I arrived in Italy,
six weeks before we started shooting,

1320
01:17:27,643 --> 01:17:31,479
I knew that I needed to find
some kind of Italian festival

1321
01:17:31,563 --> 01:17:34,190
or some kind of traditional sport

1322
01:17:34,274 --> 01:17:38,736
that Pawel could participate in
and prove his manhood through.

1323
01:17:39,321 --> 01:17:41,030
And I didn't know
what I was going to use.

1324
01:17:41,114 --> 01:17:43,658
There was archery.
There was barrel-rolling,

1325
01:17:43,742 --> 01:17:45,951
and then
I heard about the flag throwing.

1326
01:17:46,036 --> 01:17:47,870
And we went to watch it
a bunch of times.

1327
01:17:47,954 --> 01:17:49,664
And the more l watched it,

1328
01:17:49,748 --> 01:17:51,290
the more I had to
come to the conclusion

1329
01:17:51,375 --> 01:17:55,586
that it was men in tights waving flags,
and really not much more.

1330
01:17:56,088 --> 01:17:59,674
lt was nice to look at,
but it had its challenges.

1331
01:17:59,758 --> 01:18:01,926
It was hard to make Pawel

1332
01:18:02,010 --> 01:18:05,179
look very much like
a macho stud flag throwing.

1333
01:18:05,597 --> 01:18:10,184
But there is a sweetness to it,
and a sweetness to her reaction to it,

1334
01:18:11,103 --> 01:18:13,979
and it's so colorful,
I thought we could make it work.

1335
01:18:16,233 --> 01:18:17,233
Whoo!

1336
01:18:39,631 --> 01:18:41,382
Yay! Bravo!

1337
01:18:41,466 --> 01:18:45,219
WELLS: Here once again, we used
the latest special effects technology

1338
01:18:45,303 --> 01:18:47,054
to achieve our ends.

1339
01:18:47,806 --> 01:18:49,014
Somebody stood on a ladder

1340
01:18:49,099 --> 01:18:51,600
and dropped a Styrofoam pole
on Pawel's head.

1341
01:19:00,193 --> 01:19:03,237
We had two days to shoot this scene
and three cameras.

1342
01:19:03,405 --> 01:19:06,365
And, as always, my ally in this scene

1343
01:19:06,450 --> 01:19:08,909
was my director of photography,
Geoffrey Simpson.

1344
01:19:12,080 --> 01:19:15,040
-I threw the flag.
-Si, amore.

1345
01:19:18,837 --> 01:19:20,838
They're fine.

1346
01:19:22,007 --> 01:19:23,507
Let's go.

1347
01:19:27,345 --> 01:19:29,930
WELLS: GeoffSimpson wasn't
the only important cameraman

1348
01:19:30,015 --> 01:19:31,348
working on the movie for me.

1349
01:19:31,683 --> 01:19:33,934
Because the other one
was my husband,

1350
01:19:34,019 --> 01:19:36,937
who shot
a lot of the second unit material,

1351
01:19:37,272 --> 01:19:39,148
like this landscape shot right here.

1352
01:19:50,035 --> 01:19:54,163
Francesca, you see my daughter.
She seems so different.

1353
01:19:54,247 --> 01:19:55,539
Really?

1354
01:19:55,624 --> 01:19:57,958
-Chiara is not herself.
-Oh.

1355
01:19:58,043 --> 01:20:01,545
Maybe... Do you know
what's bothering her?

1356
01:20:02,714 --> 01:20:04,882
Placido, I don't know.

1357
01:20:05,509 --> 01:20:09,386
Hey, Frances, look.
You can see Bramasole from here.

1358
01:20:10,055 --> 01:20:11,263
See?

1359
01:20:11,807 --> 01:20:13,140
Thank you.

1360
01:20:21,900 --> 01:20:25,903
WELLS: Diane was always game
for whatever was required of her.

1361
01:20:26,738 --> 01:20:29,615
She threw herself into things
wholeheartedly.

1362
01:20:29,699 --> 01:20:31,909
And that included the physical comedy.

1363
01:20:32,911 --> 01:20:36,872
I really had a good time watching her
the day that we shot this scene.

1364
01:20:37,457 --> 01:20:40,042
The way she tore off down that hill.

1365
01:20:40,544 --> 01:20:45,631
And when it was time
to fall down the muddy embankment,

1366
01:20:46,091 --> 01:20:50,177
she did it with such abandon that
we only did a second take for safety,

1367
01:20:50,262 --> 01:20:52,638
because the first one was so hilarious.

1368
01:20:59,646 --> 01:21:00,771
Arh...

1369
01:21:04,276 --> 01:21:05,568
Wait!

1370
01:21:09,281 --> 01:21:11,282
Marcello!

1371
01:21:15,620 --> 01:21:17,371
WELLS: Sometimes when
l watch a scene in the film,

1372
01:21:17,455 --> 01:21:19,623
I still remember
the shooting day vividly.

1373
01:21:19,708 --> 01:21:20,875
And when l watch this scene,

1374
01:21:20,959 --> 01:21:23,419
I remember that I had a migraine
the day that we shot this.

1375
01:21:23,795 --> 01:21:25,337
And that we were
working on a Saturday,

1376
01:21:25,422 --> 01:21:28,883
which meant that the crew was only
going to work seven straight hours,

1377
01:21:28,967 --> 01:21:32,052
and that then they were going to leave
come hell or high water.

1378
01:21:32,137 --> 01:21:33,762
And it was a big scene to get done

1379
01:21:33,847 --> 01:21:36,223
and not the only one
that we had scheduled for the day.

1380
01:21:36,641 --> 01:21:39,894
And I remember
everybody starting to pack up to leave

1381
01:21:39,978 --> 01:21:44,273
while Sandra was still trying
to come up with her performance

1382
01:21:44,357 --> 01:21:46,066
for the last beat of this scene

1383
01:21:46,151 --> 01:21:49,320
when she admits
that she is already in labor.

1384
01:21:50,405 --> 01:21:53,449
When l look at it,
I remember really how mad I was.

1385
01:21:53,533 --> 01:21:57,411
(CHUCKLING) But like so many
other days of shooting on the film,

1386
01:21:57,495 --> 01:22:00,247
the behind-the-scenes action
didn't really manifest onscreen.

1387
01:22:01,666 --> 01:22:04,168
You could've tied him to a chair,
you could've crippled him!

1388
01:22:04,252 --> 01:22:07,171
You could've faked labor, at least!

1389
01:22:08,173 --> 01:22:10,716
I wouldn't have had to fake it.

1390
01:22:12,469 --> 01:22:14,011
WELLS: l remember that even
the night before

1391
01:22:14,095 --> 01:22:17,014
we were scheduled to shoot the scene,
we still didn't have a baby

1392
01:22:17,098 --> 01:22:20,976
to play Patti's infant
that was of a believable weight.

1393
01:22:21,061 --> 01:22:22,645
And I was very nervous
about finding one

1394
01:22:22,729 --> 01:22:24,271
that was young enough
and small enough

1395
01:22:24,356 --> 01:22:25,856
to be convincing as a newborn.

1396
01:22:26,691 --> 01:22:30,861
This baby was born to a couple
in Rome that was on set that day.

1397
01:22:30,946 --> 01:22:34,657
And I remember the very quiet
and reverent atmosphere on set

1398
01:22:34,741 --> 01:22:36,158
as they stood behind the camera

1399
01:22:36,242 --> 01:22:40,245
nervously watching their infant
being passed from actress to actress.

1400
01:22:41,331 --> 01:22:43,207
We didn't really
have Florence out the window.

1401
01:22:43,291 --> 01:22:44,750
That's a green screen effect.

1402
01:22:44,876 --> 01:22:47,252
So Diane wasn't really
about to heave-ho.

1403
01:22:51,091 --> 01:22:54,051
The pink ribbons on the door,
that's a tradition in Italy

1404
01:22:54,135 --> 01:22:56,428
that I was unaware of
until I started scouting.

1405
01:22:56,721 --> 01:22:59,306
It's something that they do
to announce the arrival of a baby.

1406
01:22:59,391 --> 01:23:01,892
And I thought it was a nice addition
to the scene.

1407
01:23:03,228 --> 01:23:04,937
Okay...

1408
01:23:07,315 --> 01:23:09,400
You're so cute, you're so cute!

1409
01:23:10,026 --> 01:23:11,652
WELLS: This flower design
on the ground

1410
01:23:11,736 --> 01:23:14,238
is part of something called an infiorata,

1411
01:23:14,322 --> 01:23:18,409
a festival where people make fantastic
living tapestries on the ground.

1412
01:23:18,702 --> 01:23:21,161
And my regret is that
we were so pushed for time that day

1413
01:23:21,246 --> 01:23:24,331
that I had to move on
before I got my wide shot.

1414
01:23:24,541 --> 01:23:27,626
And I still haven't really let go
of my disappointment over that.

1415
01:23:29,212 --> 01:23:31,046
Still, l think that the sequence works.

1416
01:23:31,131 --> 01:23:32,506
A baby is born,
the spring flowers bloom,

1417
01:23:33,425 --> 01:23:35,009
and the house is coming back to life.

1418
01:23:41,182 --> 01:23:43,225
Frances?

1419
01:23:45,395 --> 01:23:47,855
We are finished.

1420
01:23:55,071 --> 01:23:57,614
WELLS: l think it's very tender,
this scene.

1421
01:23:57,699 --> 01:23:59,825
The Polish guys have
become Frances' family,

1422
01:23:59,909 --> 01:24:02,661
and their work is done
and it's time for them to leave.

1423
01:24:04,122 --> 01:24:06,248
There was a detail
in Frances Mayes' book

1424
01:24:06,332 --> 01:24:10,377
in which the Polish workers
wrote the word "Polonia" on a stone

1425
01:24:10,462 --> 01:24:13,005
that they placed
near the bottom of her finished wall.

1426
01:24:13,089 --> 01:24:14,590
And I found that very touching.

1427
01:24:18,928 --> 01:24:21,597
I like the way the different actors
handle a scene.

1428
01:24:21,681 --> 01:24:26,018
I like Valentine's reserve
and continued dignity here.

1429
01:24:26,311 --> 01:24:28,562
I like the way Pawel smiles and laughs

1430
01:24:28,646 --> 01:24:30,898
kind of in counterpoint
to the emotion of the scene.

1431
01:24:32,734 --> 01:24:36,195
l had suggested to Sasa
that he might cry in this scene.

1432
01:24:36,738 --> 01:24:39,073
And this is what he did with it.

1433
01:25:07,018 --> 01:25:10,521
The traditional structure
of romantic comedy, or human comedy

1434
01:25:10,605 --> 01:25:14,274
as this film is, is that things reach
their low point at the end of Act 2.

1435
01:25:14,359 --> 01:25:16,318
There is always, at least in my writing,

1436
01:25:16,402 --> 01:25:18,320
a point at which the comedy
slows down

1437
01:25:18,404 --> 01:25:22,032
and the needs of the characters
in their most sincere form take over.

1438
01:25:22,575 --> 01:25:24,034
And we worry about Frances here.

1439
01:25:24,119 --> 01:25:26,286
Because we see that,
despite all her efforts,

1440
01:25:26,371 --> 01:25:27,538
she still feels alone.

1441
01:25:55,024 --> 01:25:56,483
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

1442
01:25:59,445 --> 01:26:03,740
I had always hoped that these boxes
of books would come as a surprise.

1443
01:26:04,159 --> 01:26:06,493
That we had forgotten about them
and that to see them now

1444
01:26:06,578 --> 01:26:08,078
would have a certain punch to it.

1445
01:26:08,830 --> 01:26:11,665
And the blue vase
functions as a hot object,

1446
01:26:11,749 --> 01:26:14,918
meaning an object
that carries a lot of emotional value

1447
01:26:15,003 --> 01:26:17,713
and symbolism for my main character.

1448
01:26:31,686 --> 01:26:33,770
This photograph represents
the only time

1449
01:26:33,855 --> 01:26:35,939
that we actually see
Frances' ex-husband.

1450
01:26:36,900 --> 01:26:40,235
I thought that creating a moving image
inside the Polaroid

1451
01:26:40,320 --> 01:26:43,030
would evoke her visceral memory
of what it was like

1452
01:26:43,114 --> 01:26:44,323
when she used to feel loved.

1453
01:26:45,408 --> 01:26:46,575
She looks at that photo

1454
01:26:46,659 --> 01:26:49,912
and she knows urgently
that she has to move on.

1455
01:26:55,251 --> 01:26:57,544
I love what Chris Beck did
with the music here,

1456
01:26:57,629 --> 01:27:00,088
creating the anticipation
for the cut to the next scene.

1457
01:27:08,306 --> 01:27:10,557
One hour before l got this shot,

1458
01:27:10,642 --> 01:27:13,143
that stone pier
was completely underwater.

1459
01:27:13,353 --> 01:27:15,854
And every time I see the shot,
I feel incredibly grateful

1460
01:27:15,939 --> 01:27:19,107
that Diane wasn't knocked over
by a wave and dragged out to sea.

1461
01:27:19,484 --> 01:27:21,235
The fact that Diane
didn't worry about her safety

1462
01:27:21,319 --> 01:27:22,903
is one of the reasons that I love her.

1463
01:27:22,987 --> 01:27:25,113
She always wanted the shot
as much as I did.

1464
01:27:29,535 --> 01:27:31,411
This sequence
on the back of the motorbike

1465
01:27:31,496 --> 01:27:34,081
was shot in about 20 frantic minutes

1466
01:27:34,165 --> 01:27:36,416
while most of the crew
was packing to leave Positano

1467
01:27:36,501 --> 01:27:37,834
when the sun was going down.

1468
01:27:38,211 --> 01:27:41,338
Johnny got it on his Steadicam
sitting on the back of a Polaris.

1469
01:27:44,968 --> 01:27:48,178
And once again, Diane eschewed
safety and didn't wear a helmet,

1470
01:27:48,263 --> 01:27:50,847
so that we could see all that
beautiful hair flowing in the wind.

1471
01:27:55,353 --> 01:27:57,646
There were a lot of challenges
getting this scene done.

1472
01:27:57,981 --> 01:28:01,275
For one thing, we all thought that
Raoul Bova's fans would show up,

1473
01:28:01,359 --> 01:28:03,110
and we were afraid that
we would be surrounded

1474
01:28:03,194 --> 01:28:06,113
by a thousand young women
screaming, "Raoul, Raoul."

1475
01:28:06,197 --> 01:28:08,198
But, fortunately, they didn't materialize.

1476
01:28:08,700 --> 01:28:12,119
But even without the fans,
this was a tough shooting day.

1477
01:28:12,745 --> 01:28:14,705
We battled the elements
getting this scene.

1478
01:28:14,789 --> 01:28:17,040
The clouds were
moving incredibly fast.

1479
01:28:17,125 --> 01:28:20,377
And every take went in and out
of sun every 30 seconds.

1480
01:28:20,878 --> 01:28:24,381
Geoff was calling out F-stop changes
while the actors were performing.

1481
01:28:24,465 --> 01:28:27,843
And it rained maybe six times
during Diane's coverage.

1482
01:28:28,219 --> 01:28:30,929
And PAs kept running out
with umbrellas to shield her.

1483
01:28:31,597 --> 01:28:35,475
Plus we were on a tiny road
that was the only road out of Positano.

1484
01:28:35,768 --> 01:28:37,269
And when we weren't
stopping for the sun,

1485
01:28:37,353 --> 01:28:38,895
we were stopping to let the traffic out.

1486
01:28:39,647 --> 01:28:41,273
It was stressful for the actors.

1487
01:28:41,357 --> 01:28:42,899
And when we were done shooting,

1488
01:28:42,984 --> 01:28:45,944
I was unconvinced
that the scene would ever cut.

1489
01:28:46,237 --> 01:28:49,573
And the fact that it works
is due to Geoff's quick reactions,

1490
01:28:49,657 --> 01:28:52,909
my editor and the color timer
at Technicolor, Lee Wimer.

1491
01:28:53,119 --> 01:28:56,413
I sent her a really good bottle of wine
after this.

1492
01:29:02,837 --> 01:29:04,880
Wow, I...

1493
01:29:07,300 --> 01:29:09,051
I came at a bad time.

1494
01:29:09,135 --> 01:29:12,012
Francesca, wait. Wait. Wait.

1495
01:29:12,096 --> 01:29:15,098
I'm sorry you're hurt.
But what did you expect?

1496
01:29:15,183 --> 01:29:17,184
What did I expect?

1497
01:29:17,560 --> 01:29:20,354
You came to Bramasole.
You left that note.

1498
01:29:20,438 --> 01:29:23,565
-I thought... I thought that you...
-Just a minute, just a minute.

1499
01:29:23,649 --> 01:29:25,776
Months ago, we had a beautiful affair.

1500
01:29:25,860 --> 01:29:28,195
WELLS: The dialogue in this scene
was a little tricky to write.

1501
01:29:28,279 --> 01:29:30,530
It's an inherently melodramatic scene,

1502
01:29:30,615 --> 01:29:33,367
but there is truth in it, l think,
and that's what saves it.

1503
01:29:34,160 --> 01:29:37,204
Of course, Frances' affair
with the fantasy man can't work out.

1504
01:29:37,288 --> 01:29:40,374
And if it had, this movie
would've been entirely different,

1505
01:29:40,458 --> 01:29:42,459
with a different meaning
and a different tone.

1506
01:29:43,336 --> 01:29:46,713
As it is, the scene shows,
l think, a realistic end

1507
01:29:46,798 --> 01:29:49,257
to what was essentially
an unrealistic affair.

1508
01:29:49,717 --> 01:29:51,802
There was my friend,
and she was going to have a baby...

1509
01:29:51,886 --> 01:29:54,513
There were many, many other things.

1510
01:29:56,474 --> 01:29:59,226
Important things you had to do.

1511
01:30:00,603 --> 01:30:02,646
And you couldn't wait.

1512
01:30:03,314 --> 01:30:06,233
WELLS: I didn't want Raoul's character
to end up as the bad guy.

1513
01:30:06,734 --> 01:30:10,278
I tried to construct dialogue
that was fair to both characters.

1514
01:30:10,738 --> 01:30:14,157
And I think what Marcello is saying
in this scene has integrity.

1515
01:30:14,283 --> 01:30:17,953
Raoul felt that his character
was full of sincere regret.

1516
01:30:18,704 --> 01:30:20,789
We did about seven takes on Raoul

1517
01:30:20,873 --> 01:30:23,417
with the clouds blowing wildly
across the sun,

1518
01:30:23,876 --> 01:30:26,336
but each take was
wonderfully nuanced

1519
01:30:26,421 --> 01:30:27,712
and sort of heartbreaking.

1520
01:30:27,797 --> 01:30:29,673
There is someone for you, Francesca.

1521
01:30:41,436 --> 01:30:43,437
Goodbye.

1522
01:30:51,487 --> 01:30:52,863
Francesca.

1523
01:31:12,925 --> 01:31:15,385
WELLS: This scene, which we just
called "the fountain scene,"

1524
01:31:15,470 --> 01:31:18,180
was the one I was most concerned
about pulling off.

1525
01:31:18,723 --> 01:31:20,557
Asking an actress to do her impression

1526
01:31:20,641 --> 01:31:23,602
ofAnita Ekberg in La Dolce Vita
is a tall order.

1527
01:31:23,895 --> 01:31:25,103
It was really pretty risky.

1528
01:31:25,229 --> 01:31:28,732
And I knew that we'd be referencing
one of the most famous love scenes

1529
01:31:28,816 --> 01:31:31,318
in cinema history. It's not the kind
of thing you want to get wrong.

1530
01:31:32,111 --> 01:31:35,489
But Lindsay,
with the costuming help of Nicoletta,

1531
01:31:35,573 --> 01:31:36,823
she really pulled it off.

1532
01:31:37,450 --> 01:31:39,034
It had been freezing and windy as hell.

1533
01:31:39,118 --> 01:31:40,744
But for some reason,
it warmed up that night

1534
01:31:40,828 --> 01:31:42,621
and the air was completely still.

1535
01:31:42,705 --> 01:31:44,873
And I remember feeling that
that was a good omen.

1536
01:31:48,920 --> 01:31:50,086
Is she drunk?

1537
01:31:50,171 --> 01:31:53,507
WELLS: We dressed Vince in a
black suit like Marcello Mastroianni.

1538
01:31:53,591 --> 01:31:56,635
And I think he and Diane
have perfect comic timing here.

1539
01:31:58,095 --> 01:32:00,764
Chris Beck's score also
gives the scene a lot of help.

1540
01:32:00,932 --> 01:32:03,266
He composed something
very eerie and beautiful

1541
01:32:03,351 --> 01:32:06,520
that was very much related
to the kind of scores

1542
01:32:06,604 --> 01:32:08,563
that Nino Rota did for Fellini.

1543
01:32:13,778 --> 01:32:15,987
(APPLAUSE AND CHEERING)

1544
01:32:18,449 --> 01:32:20,033
Then, of course,
there is the fountain itself,

1545
01:32:20,117 --> 01:32:23,537
which l think is Stephen McCabe's
crowning achievement in the film.

1546
01:32:23,621 --> 01:32:26,248
There was no fountain
in the Piazza Signorelli in Cortona,

1547
01:32:26,332 --> 01:32:28,542
and Steve knew
that I wanted something

1548
01:32:28,626 --> 01:32:32,504
in a heroic classical form
like the Trevi Fountain in Rome.

1549
01:32:33,464 --> 01:32:37,384
He designed this statue and we built it
from scratch out of fiberglass.

1550
01:32:38,553 --> 01:32:40,053
That's the royal "we," of course,

1551
01:32:40,137 --> 01:32:42,639
because I personally
didn't get my hands dirty.

1552
01:32:44,308 --> 01:32:48,061
When the fountain was first installed,
the town was scandalized to see

1553
01:32:48,145 --> 01:32:51,314
that the male figure sported an
anatomically proportionate package,

1554
01:32:52,358 --> 01:32:55,110
and it caused such a scandal
that the local paper

1555
01:32:55,194 --> 01:32:57,237
accused me of being
a Communist sympathizer,

1556
01:32:57,321 --> 01:32:58,905
because the statue hung left.

1557
01:32:58,990 --> 01:33:01,283
At which point,
l decided to order a reduction,

1558
01:33:01,367 --> 01:33:03,618
which I heard was carried out
under the cover of night.

1559
01:33:06,747 --> 01:33:08,832
Do you think I make a good Sylvia?

1560
01:33:09,041 --> 01:33:11,126
You were wonderful.

1561
01:33:15,006 --> 01:33:16,673
Here.

1562
01:33:18,384 --> 01:33:21,428
WELLS: This is the scene that makes
Katherine's character work for me.

1563
01:33:22,179 --> 01:33:24,973
Without this scene,
Katherine is an eccentric

1564
01:33:25,057 --> 01:33:28,184
who suffers some kind
of narcissistic delusions.

1565
01:33:28,561 --> 01:33:31,104
But with this scene,
we realize that Katherine

1566
01:33:31,188 --> 01:33:35,900
has made a conscious choice to live
in her flamboyant and grand style.

1567
01:33:36,986 --> 01:33:38,778
She is not a marginal,

1568
01:33:38,863 --> 01:33:43,366
almost psychotic person
caught in fantasies and delusions,

1569
01:33:43,784 --> 01:33:46,953
she is a real woman
who has made decisions

1570
01:33:47,038 --> 01:33:48,955
about how she is going to handle pain
in her life.

1571
01:33:49,040 --> 01:33:52,417
And how she is going
to incorporate joy.

1572
01:33:53,961 --> 01:33:57,172
And here with the monologue
that she has at the end of the scene,

1573
01:33:57,256 --> 01:33:59,382
I think we really understand
what makes her tick.

1574
01:34:05,181 --> 01:34:09,976
You know who I really love the most
from all the films?

1575
01:34:10,936 --> 01:34:12,395
Cabiria.

1576
01:34:14,440 --> 01:34:16,775
You remember at the end,

1577
01:34:16,859 --> 01:34:20,987
when another man has left her
in the most terrible way,

1578
01:34:21,072 --> 01:34:24,032
and she thinks it's all over for her?

1579
01:34:25,576 --> 01:34:30,997
Then she sees some children
playing in the street, making music,

1580
01:34:32,249 --> 01:34:36,920
and before she knows it,
she's smiling again.

1581
01:34:40,257 --> 01:34:42,550
That's what Fefe always said,

1582
01:34:43,969 --> 01:34:46,429
"No matter what happens,

1583
01:34:48,933 --> 01:34:52,268
"always keep your childish innocence.

1584
01:34:53,938 --> 01:34:57,941
"It's the most important thing."

1585
01:35:14,625 --> 01:35:16,376
WELLS: When Frances
returns to the house,

1586
01:35:16,460 --> 01:35:19,462
we see that the entryway
has remained the same

1587
01:35:19,547 --> 01:35:22,048
since the day
that she first arrived at Bramasole.

1588
01:35:22,633 --> 01:35:25,009
It signals that the house
is still incomplete,

1589
01:35:25,428 --> 01:35:27,178
as is Frances' journey.

1590
01:35:27,471 --> 01:35:29,931
I can't... I can't talk about it now.

1591
01:35:30,015 --> 01:35:31,474
Fran...

1592
01:35:36,105 --> 01:35:39,941
WELLS: I think Frances is almost
frighteningly miserable in this scene.

1593
01:35:40,443 --> 01:35:44,446
She's reached her lowest
and most faithless moment.

1594
01:35:45,156 --> 01:35:48,116
But that's also when everything
can start turning around for her.

1595
01:35:50,035 --> 01:35:52,495
Stupid. Stupid.

1596
01:35:52,580 --> 01:35:55,999
WELLS: Once again,
I think we only shot this scene twice.

1597
01:35:56,250 --> 01:35:59,419
Diane doesn't need to do something
like this over and over.

1598
01:35:59,503 --> 01:36:03,131
The very first time she does it,
she is entirely emotionally prepared.

1599
01:36:09,513 --> 01:36:10,930
(SOBBING OUTSIDE)

1600
01:36:39,043 --> 01:36:41,044
This is the scene
that almost didn't happen.

1601
01:36:41,128 --> 01:36:43,505
It was our very last day of shooting.

1602
01:36:43,589 --> 01:36:45,548
And we worked from maybe

1603
01:36:45,633 --> 01:36:47,967
4:00 in the afternoon
until 4:00 in the morning.

1604
01:36:49,345 --> 01:36:52,180
EveIina Gori,
the grandmother character,

1605
01:36:52,264 --> 01:36:55,141
she had had a heart attack
about six weeks earlier

1606
01:36:55,226 --> 01:36:57,936
after having shot most of her scenes.

1607
01:36:59,271 --> 01:37:01,940
There were people who felt
that she should not return to work,

1608
01:37:02,024 --> 01:37:05,068
that she shouldn't be in this scene
and she shouldn't complete the movie.

1609
01:37:05,903 --> 01:37:08,613
I felt differently about it.
If Evelina was up for it,

1610
01:37:08,697 --> 01:37:12,242
I wanted to fight to keep her
in the scene and not to rewrite it.

1611
01:37:12,868 --> 01:37:15,829
I respected her a lot,
she'd been an actress her entire life.

1612
01:37:15,913 --> 01:37:19,415
And we both felt that this might be
her last role before she retired.

1613
01:37:19,917 --> 01:37:22,418
And I thought it was important
that she complete the movie

1614
01:37:22,503 --> 01:37:26,381
for me, of course, and for the film.
But also, out of respect for Evelina.

1615
01:37:28,843 --> 01:37:33,263
The fact that she could only
come to work on this particular day,

1616
01:37:33,347 --> 01:37:37,016
this last day, conflicted
with Anita Zagaria's schedule,

1617
01:37:37,101 --> 01:37:39,185
that's the actress that plays the mother.

1618
01:37:39,687 --> 01:37:41,563
And she was working
on another movie that day

1619
01:37:41,647 --> 01:37:43,356
and couldn't start until the afternoon.

1620
01:37:44,108 --> 01:37:46,943
Diane had been fulfilling commitments
on Unfaithful

1621
01:37:47,027 --> 01:37:50,864
in England that weekend and had to
fly back for this last day of shooting.

1622
01:37:51,198 --> 01:37:53,116
It was freezing cold and pouring rain.

1623
01:37:53,200 --> 01:37:55,326
Everyone was tired.
Tensions were high.

1624
01:37:55,536 --> 01:37:58,079
And it was one of the most important
scenes in the movie.

1625
01:37:58,873 --> 01:38:00,290
Wait.

1626
01:38:03,419 --> 01:38:04,836
Won't you give your blessing?

1627
01:38:05,629 --> 01:38:07,672
What if this is it?

1628
01:38:08,007 --> 01:38:12,552
The real thing. A love that lasts forever.

1629
01:38:12,636 --> 01:38:16,556
-What you describe is only in fairy tales.
-No, it's not.

1630
01:38:16,640 --> 01:38:20,393
And how do you know?
From personal experience?

1631
01:38:21,270 --> 01:38:25,273
WELLS: When l first wrote this scene
and I realized that by the end of it

1632
01:38:25,357 --> 01:38:28,568
Frances was going to claim Pawel
as part of her family,

1633
01:38:28,819 --> 01:38:31,487
the themes of the film
really gelled for me.

1634
01:38:32,156 --> 01:38:33,156
I thought it was meaningful

1635
01:38:33,240 --> 01:38:35,909
that Frances was fighting
for the happiness of others

1636
01:38:35,993 --> 01:38:37,493
even in the midst of her misery.

1637
01:38:37,995 --> 01:38:40,663
And I thought that
she was creating her salvation,

1638
01:38:40,873 --> 01:38:42,165
even though she didn't realize that.

1639
01:38:43,167 --> 01:38:44,792
Mamma, Mamma!

1640
01:38:49,757 --> 01:38:51,674
He has no family!

1641
01:38:54,011 --> 01:38:56,012
That's not true.

1642
